s reopened its doors |work=[[France Info (TV channel)|France Info]] |language=French |accessdate=20 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last1=Phillips |editor1-first=Alastair |editor-last2=Vincendeau |editor2-first=Ginette |year=2013 |chapter=Filmography |title=A Companion to Jean Renoir |location=Oxford |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |pp=572\u2013584 |isbn=978-1-4443-3853-9 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1974 |title=My Life and My Films |translator-last=Denny |translator-first=Norman |location=New York |publisher=Da Capo Press |isbn=0-306-80457-3 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Renoir |first=Jean |year=1989 |title=Renoir on Renoir: Interviews, Essays, and Remarks |translator-last=Volk |translator-first=Carol |location=Cambridge |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=0-521-38593-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite journal |last=Rohmer |first=\u00c9ric |authorlink=\u00c9ric Rohmer |date=December 1959 |title=Jeunesse de Jean Renoir |trans-title=Jean Renoir's youth |journal=Cahiers du cin\u00e9ma |language=French |issue=102 |pp=1\u20137 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |editor-last=Rivi\u00e8re |editor-first=Marie-Sylvie |year=2018 |chapter-url=https://services.jamesnook.com/services/storage?type=document&id=225222&secret=PDEc67rdlHn3SI3XwAYQIplX2qRvfq61spuq6eE4 |chapter=Go\u00fbter l'Europe |trans-chapter=Taste Europe |title=Quelle Europe voulons-nous ? En suppl\u00e9ment: une s\u00e9lection d'articles et d'entretiens |trans-title=What Europe do we want? Supplement: a selection of articles and interviews |language=French |location=Paris |publisher=Semaines sociales de France |pp=45\u201357 |isbn=9782322102792 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite book |last=Silke |first=James R. |year=2005 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vmMH_muqTycC&pg=PA134 |chapter=Jean Renoir on Love, Hollywood, Authors, and Critics |editor-last=Cardullo |editor-first=Bert |title=Jean Renoir: Interviews |location=Jackson, Mississippi |publisher=University Press of Mississippi |isbn=1-57806-730-8 |ref=harv }}\n\n: {{cite web |author=''Time Out'' |authorlink=Time Out (magazine) |url=https://www.timeout.com/london/film/le-dejeuner-sur-lherbe |title=Le D\u00e9jeuner sur l'Herbe |accessdate=2 March 2020 |ref=harv }}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0052765}}\n* {{Amg movie|38085|Picnic on the Grass}}\n\n{{Jean Renoir}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Picnic On The Grass}}\n[[Category:1959 films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jean Renoir]]\n[[Category:1950s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1950s satirical films]]\n[[Category:Artificial insemination]]\n[[Category:French romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:French satirical films]]\n[[Category:Films based on Greco-Roman mythology]]\n[[Category:Eugenics in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Gatoclass", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePre-production:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picnic_on_the_Grass"}
{"title_page": "DJ Isis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{more footnotes|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Isis van der Wel\n| image =1001 Vrouwen - DJ Isis (2).jpg\n| caption =\n| image_size =\n| background = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|04|29}}\n| alias = Isis\n| origin = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| death_date =\n| genre = [[Dance music|Dance]] <br /> [[Tech House]] <br /> [[House music|House]] <br /> [[Ambient House]] <br /> [[Techno]]\n| Musical_style =\n| occupation = DJ, DVJ, CEO\n| years_active = 1987 - present\n| label = All is One Records\n}}\n\n'''Isis van der Wel''' (born 29 April 1975 in [[Amsterdam]]), better known by her stage name '''Isis''' (previously '''''100% Isis'''''), is a Dutch [[Disc jockey|DJ]].\n\n==100% Isis==\nVan der Wel had already been assigned the stage name ''100% Isis'' when she started her performance career at age 17 with a residency at Amsterdam club [[RoXY]] from 1992 -1994. This launched her long running International career, performing at dance venues and festivals in Europe, South America, Asia, and Africa. In 1992 she performed at a [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] concert in [[Brussels]]. Together with Eric Nouhan, Isis received her first production assignment in 1995 given by [[Bols (brand)|Bols]]. From 1995 until 2000 Isis became a resident DJ at Amsterdam club ''Chemistry'' (aka 'Escape', [[Rembrandtplein]]). In 1995 she was contracted by [[EMI]], [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], [[Ariola]], and [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]. In 1996 and 1997 Isis\u2019 mix albums (\"100% Isis 1\" and \"100% Isis 2\") were ranked on various Electronic dance music national top ten charts. At the World [[Expo '98]] in Lisbon Portugal, Isis performed as an official representative of the Netherlands. Isis was subsequently asked to perform during [[Holland Festival]] in 2000. Her mix album \"Reformation\" was ranked in the top ten mix albums of 2001. In 2002 her talent was recognized globally and she was ranked in top ten of worldwide female Tech-House DJ's. In 2003 she was ranked in the top 600 of the best DJ's worldwide. At the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference|World Climate Summit 2009 in Copenhagen]] Isis achieved her audience capacity record, reaching up to 100,000 spectators.\nCrown Prince [[Willem Alexander]] was among the audience in 2010 as a special guest during an audio-visual performance by Isis at the [[Ridderzaal]].\n\n==Magma the Agency and All Is One==\nIn 2000 Isis van der Wel founded the event production and artist management company called \u2018Magma the Agency\u2019. Since 2003 Magma the Agency is organizing events under the name of 'All Is One'. Isis becomes responsible for programming and hosting an area at the world-renowned [[Mysteryland|Mystery Land]] festival from 2003 through 2008. With 'All Is One' she hosts successful events and club nights, such as All Is One Weekend and Amsterdams Glorie. Furthermore, Isis is commissioned as an art director and promoter for events like [[Amsterdam dance event]] and Museumnacht Amsterdam.\n\n==All Is One Records==\nIn 2006 \u2018All Is One Records\u2019 was officially established. In 2008 'All is One' celebrated its first releases and presents the productions of young upcoming DJs and producers such as Arjuna Schiks and Daniel Zuur. The singles released build a bridge between different genres like [[Techno]], [[House music|House]], [[Ambient music|Ambient]] and [[Experimental music|Experimental]] [[Dance music]].\n\n==Ambassador of Liberty==\nThe [[Nationaal Comit\u00e9 4 en 5 mei|national 5 May committee]] declared Isis as ''Ambassador of Liberty'' for the May 5 Dutch Independence day of 2009. This honourable title allowed her to join the queen for the annual May 4 [[Remembrance of the Dead|Remembrance ceremony]], continued by performing five big shows throughout the country on the next day, when May 5 national liberation day music festivals are held in prominent cities throughout the country.\n\n==Nachtburgemeester Amsterdam (Nightlife Ambassador)==\nIsis was elected as the Nachtburgermeester of Amsterdam (Nightlife Ambassador) in 2010, and served as such for its 2-year term. Her function was to monitor the nightlife of Amsterdam and to build bridges between local politicians, entrepreneurs, artists and its audience. During her term she joined, and continued to be a part of, an expert team led by [[Eberhard van der Laan]] (Mayor of Amsterdam) to approve 24-hour permits for specific dance venues throughout the city.\n\n==Magneet Festival==\nAnother result of Isis\u2019 Ambassadorship is the realization of the Magneet festival. Magneet Festival is a crowd-sourced festival that uses an online co-creation platform in order to assist in the programming of the event, a pioneering concept in Europe.\n\n==Zevenmanschap==\nIn 2011 she joined the \u2018Zevenmanschap\u2019, a committee headed by [[Andr\u00e9e van Es]] and aimed at raising awareness of tolerance and discrimination in Amsterdam. It consists of seven key figures from Amsterdam of diverse cultural and religious backgrounds.\n\n==Lifetime achievement award==\nIsis wins the Life Time Achievement Award in 2011 during the annual GK Awards for her outstanding achievements during her career as a prominent professional in the Dutch nightlife. Currently, Isis is extending her career to television, where she appears in several [[BNN (Dutch broadcaster)|BNN]] TV shows, like \u2018Vier Handen op 1 Buik\u2019.\n\n==20-Year Anniversary==\nIn April 2012, Isis celebrated her 20th year in the DJ business in [[Paradiso (Amsterdam)|Paradiso]], marking her overall time in the business as one of the first professional women in worldwide dance culture, as well as an important member of the Dutch nightlife scene.\n\n==From 100% Isis to Isis==\nIn August 2006 Isis decided to change her alias. When she started back in 1991, she got the name ''100% Isis''. After 15 years she decided to stop using it and she prefers to be called ''Isis'' ever since. What she had to say about it:\n\n{{quote|100% ISIS has been my nickname since I was sixteen years old, like [[Lange Frans (rapper)|Lange Frans]] & [[50 Cent]] are aliases. I didn\u2019t come up with it. The printshop which printed the very first flyer that featured me used the name 100% ISIS. And there was no stopping it ever since. I am now at a point in my career that it\u2019s time to make my name known as more than just an artist, but also as a human being which went through major developments. I am now a grown woman and my name is Isis. }}\n\n==DJ Mix CDs==\nThe following albums were top 10 nationally ranked.\n* 100% Isis  (EMI/Virgin/Ariola/BMG)\n* 100% Isis 2 (EMI/Virgin/Ariola/BMG)\n* Reformation (NEWS)\n* Pulse    (OXFAM NOVIB/ID&T/DANCETUNES)\n\nAll revenue collected from 'Pulse' goes to Girls' Power Initiative, a project for young girls in [[Nigeria]].\n\n==Discography==\n* Oriental Illusion - Isis & Eric Nouhanb - Bols 1995\n* Eenhoorn - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2008\n* Ibiza Luna - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2009\n* Blandas - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2009\n* Libert\u00e9 - ISIS - All is One Records 2009\n* Libert\u00e9 Remixes \u2013 ISIS \u2013 All is One Records 2009\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.djisis.nl/ Official website - DJ Isis]\n* [http://www.allisone.nl/ Official website - All is One]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100515102223/http://magmatheagency.com/ Official website - Magma / Boekingen]\n* [[:nl:DJ Isis|DJ Isis Wikipedia - Dutch Version]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isis, Dj}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch DJs]]\n[[Category:Female DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2010}}\n{{more footnotes|date=April 2010}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Isis van der Wel\n| image =1001 Vrouwen - DJ Isis (2).jpg\n| caption =\n| image_size =\n| background = non_performing_personnel\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1975|04|29}}\n| alias = Isis\n| origin = [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]]\n| death_date =\n| genre = [[Dance music|Dance]] <br /> [[Tech House]] <br /> [[House music|House]] <br /> [[Ambient House]] <br /> [[Techno]]\n| Musical_style =\n| occupation = DJ, DVJ, CEO\n| years_active = 1987 - present\n| label = All is One Records\n}}\n\n'''Isis van der Wel''' (born 29 April 1975 in [[Amsterdam]]), better known by her stage name '''Isis''' (previously '''''100% Isis'''''), is a Dutch [[Disc jockey|DJ]].\n\n==100% Isis==\nVan der Wel had already been assigned the stage name ''100% Isis'' when she started her performance career at age 17 with a residency at Amsterdam club [[RoXY]] from 1992 -1994. This launched her long running International career, performing at dance venues and festivals in Europe, South America, Asia, and Africa. In 1992 she performed at a [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] concert in [[Brussels]]. Together with Eric Nouhan, Isis received her first production assignment in 1995 given by [[Bols (brand)|Bols]]. From 1995 until 2000 Isis became a resident DJ at Amsterdam club ''Chemistry'' (aka 'Escape', [[Rembrandtplein]]). In 1995 she was contracted by [[EMI]], [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], [[Ariola]], and [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]. In 1996 and 1997 Isis\u2019 mix albums (\"100% Isis 1\" and \"100% Isis 2\") were ranked on various Electronic dance music national top ten charts. At the World [[Expo '98]] in Lisbon Portugal, Isis performed as an official representative of the Netherlands. Isis was subsequently asked to perform during [[Holland Festival]] in 2000. Her mix album \"Reformation\" was ranked in the top ten mix albums of 2001. In 2002 her talent was recognized globally and she was ranked in top ten of worldwide female Tech-House DJ's. In 2003 she was ranked in the top 600 of the best DJ's worldwide. At the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference|World Climate Summit 2009 in Copenhagen]] Isis achieved her audience capacity record, reaching up to 100,000 spectators.\nCrown Prince [[Willem Alexander]] was among the audience in 2010 as a special guest during an audio-visual performance by Isis at the [[Ridderzaal]].\n\n==Magma the Agency and All Is One==\nIn 2000 Isis van der Wel founded the event production and artist management company called \u2018Magma the Agency\u2019. Since 2003 Magma the Agency is organizing events under the name of 'All Is One'. Isis becomes responsible for programming and hosting an area at the world-renowned [[Mysteryland|Mystery Land]] festival from 2003 through 2008. With 'All Is One' she hosts successful events and club nights, such as All Is One Weekend and Amsterdams Glorie. Furthermore, Isis is commissioned as an art director and promoter for events like [[Amsterdam dance event]] and Museumnacht Amsterdam.\n\n==All Is One Records==\nIn 2006 \u2018All Is One Records\u2019 was officially established. In 2008 'All is One' celebrated its first releases and presents the productions of young upcoming DJs and producers such as Arjuna Schiks and Daniel Zuur. The singles released build a bridge between different genres like [[Techno]], [[House music|House]], [[Ambient music|Ambient]] and [[Experimental music|Experimental]] [[Dance music]].\n\n==Ambassador of Liberty==\nThe [[Nationaal Comit\u00e9 4 en 5 mei|national 5 May committee]] declared Isis as ''Ambassador of Liberty'' for the May 5 Dutch Independence day of 2009. This honourable title allowed her to join the queen for the annual May 4 [[Remembrance of the Dead|Remembrance ceremony]], continued by performing five big shows throughout the country on the next day, when May 5 national liberation day music festivals are held in prominent cities throughout the country.\n\n==Nachtburgemeester Amsterdam (Nightlife Ambassador)==\nIsis was elected as the Nachtburgermeester of Amsterdam (Nightlife Ambassador) in 2010, and served as such for its 2-year term. Her function was to monitor the nightlife of Amsterdam and to build bridges between local politicians, entrepreneurs, artists and its audience. During her term she joined, and continued to be a part of, an expert team led by [[Eberhard van der Laan]] (Mayor of Amsterdam) to approve 24-hour permits for specific dance venues throughout the city.\n\n==Magneet Festival==\nAnother result of Isis\u2019 Ambassadorship is the realization of the Magneet festival. Magneet Festival is a crowd-sourced festival that uses an online co-creation platform in order to assist in the programming of the event, a pioneering concept in Europe.\n\n==Zevenmanschap==\nIn 2011 she joined the \u2018Zevenmanschap\u2019, a committee headed by [[Andr\u00e9e van Es]] and aimed at raising awareness of tolerance and discrimination in Amsterdam. It consists of seven key figures from Amsterdam of diverse cultural and religious backgrounds.\n\n==Lifetime achievement award==\nIsis wins the Life Time Achievement Award in 2011 during the annual GK Awards for her outstanding achievements during her career as a prominent professional in the Dutch nightlife. Currently, Isis is extending her career to television, where she appears in several [[BNN (Dutch broadcaster)|BNN]] TV shows, like \u2018Vier Handen op 1 Buik\u2019.\n\n==20-Year Anniversary==\nIn April 2012, Isis celebrated her 20th year in the DJ business in [[Paradiso (Amsterdam)|Paradiso]], marking her overall time in the business as one of the first professional women in worldwide dance culture, as well as an important member of the Dutch nightlife scene.\n\n==From 100% Isis to Isis==\nIn August 2006 Isis decided to change her alias. When she started back in 1991, she got the name ''100% Isis''. After 15 years she decided to stop using it and she prefers to be called ''Isis'' ever since. What she had to say about it:\n\n{{quote|100% ISIS has been my nickname since I was sixteen years old, like [[Lange Frans (rapper)|Lange Frans]] & [[50 Cent]] are aliases. I didn\u2019t come up with it. The printshop which printed the very first flyer that featured me used the name 100% ISIS. And there was no stopping it ever since. I am now at a point in my career that it\u2019s time to make my name known as more than just an artist, but also as a human being which went through major developments. I am now a grown woman and my name is Isis. }}\n\n==DJ Mix CDs==\nThe following albums were top 10 nationally ranked.\n* 100% Isis  (EMI/Vigin/Ariola/BMG)\n* 100% Isis 2 (EMI/Virgin/Ariola/BMG)\n* Reformation (NEWS)\n* Pulse    (OXFAM NOVIB/ID&T/DANCETUNES)\n\nAll revenue collected from 'Pulse' goes to Girls' Power Initiative, a project for young girls in [[Nigeria]].\n\n==Discography==\n* Oriental Illusion - Isis & Eric Nouhanb - Bols 1995\n* Eenhoorn - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2008\n* Ibiza Luna - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2009\n* Blandas - ISIS & Piet Jan Blauw - All is One Records 2009\n* Libert\u00e9 - ISIS - All is One Records 2009\n* Libert\u00e9 Remixes \u2013 ISIS \u2013 All is One Records 2009\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.djisis.nl/ Official website - DJ Isis]\n* [http://www.allisone.nl/ Official website - All is One]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100515102223/http://magmatheagency.com/ Official website - Magma / Boekingen]\n* [[:nl:DJ Isis|DJ Isis Wikipedia - Dutch Version]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Isis, Dj}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch DJs]]\n[[Category:Female DJs]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:21st-century women musicians]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDJ Mix CDs:Typo fixing, replaced: Vigin \u2192 Virgin", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DJ_Isis"}
{"title_page": "NCAA Football 07", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=NCAA Football 07\n|image=NCAA Football 07 Coverart.jpg\n|developer=[[EA Tiburon]]\n|publisher=[[EA Sports]]\n|designer=\n|engine=\n|released=July 18, 2006\n|genre=[[Sports game|Sports]], [[American football]]\n|modes=[[single-player video game|Single player]], [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]], multiplayer online\n|platforms=[[PlayStation 2|PS2]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Xbox 360]], [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]]\n}}\n\n'''''NCAA Football 07''''' is a [[college football|collegiate football]] [[video game]] published by [[Electronic Arts]]. It is the successor to ''[[NCAA Football 06]]'' in the ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]'' series. The product features former [[University of Southern California|USC]] player [[Reggie Bush]] on the cover. While there weren't any new, major features added to the PlayStation 2 and Xbox games, tweaks were added to improve the existing features.\n\nThe theme for ''07'' is \"Turn the Tide\". Like [[NCAA Football 2005|the 2005 version]] said for home-field advantage, this year's version emphasizes that momentum is more important in college football than any other sport. This is illustrated by a momentum meter on the score graphic at the top (or bottom, in the case of the Xbox 360 version) of the screen. The more the meter is shifted towards a team, the better its players will perform (ex. If the momentum bar is all the way full with a +5 number below it (or above it), all players on the team will have their attributes boosted 5 points).\n\n''NCAA Football 07'' also includes spring drills, an update to Race for the Heisman mode called Campus Legend (which plays more like NFL Superstar mode in ''[[Madden NFL 07|Madden]]''), [[ESPN]] integration, and a spring game in Dynasty and Campus Legend modes. ESPN integration is expected to increase with the next NCAA Football releases.\n\n\n==Campus Legend==\n\nCampus Legend, for the most part, runs on the same system as its predecessor, Race for the Heisman. One creates a player, goes to a football camp, performs in drills, and is awarded a scholarship to play for a Division 1-A program. However, changes begin right from the start of camp. \n<sup>Campus Legend was not available on the Xbox 360 Version of the game.</sup>\n\n===Camp===\nRather than picking one drill to participate in, the player participates in a series of four drills which vary by position. (e.g. player gains attribute points - one to sixteen points depending on the performance - by repeatedly tapping A on the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] during the 40 Yard Dash.)\n\nPick a college\n\n[[Image:Ncaa 2007 screenshot.jpg|left|thumb|300px|Screenshot of in-game action between [[Virginia Tech]] and [[University of Virginia|Virginia]] at [[ Stadium]]]]\nAnother change in ''NCAA Football 07'' is which schools you can attend. Rather than choosing one of three scholarships or applying as a walk-on to another program, performance in camp determines your points and the distribution of those to your player will determine the caliber of your player (between one and five stars). This, in turn, determines how many of the 119 schools one can sign with and how highly those teams are ranked that you sign with. For example, a five-star recruit has the option to sign with any Division 1-A program of any rank and has a 50% popularity bonus, while a four-star recruit can sign with any Division 1-A program without the bonus. The lower the caliber, the fewer schools and lower rank one can choose from.\n\n===The Dorm===\nOnce moved into the dorm, a player is required to choose a major. While some are legitimate (e.g. chemistry, sports medicine, English), others are rather odd (e.g. [[ESPN]], 1-AA team nicknames, sports geography). Academic performance will improve a player's ratings, but one must choose a major that improves relevant ratings. For example, a quarterback would not want to major in something that would improve his tackling ability. In your dorm room, there is also a fan mailbox, where you can read generated mail from your fans. Also added is an NCAA progress report, where you can check your GPA, athletic goals, attribute point bonuses, and popularity; a computer to check rankings anywhere from the Heisman watch to All-Americans to the coaches' and AP polls; a closet to edit appearance, gear, and attribute points; and a school magazine chronicling headlines from your team (or, in case of a senior year, they will boast about the player).  The dorm room also featured a picture of the player's current girlfriend, with the beauty depending on the player's success; this feature was removed for the NCAA football 08 edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/780/780221p1.html |title=NCAA Football 08 Preview |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n\n===During the year===\nCampus Legend introduces a challenge for the player to balance academic performance, athletic performance, and campus popularity in hopes of becoming the greatest to ever attend his school. Each weekday on the calendar in the dorm has a morning, afternoon, and evening event. The morning event is always classes (with the exception of the midterm and final exams), and is automatically simulated (unless it's an aforementioned test). The afternoon event is always practice, where one can earn attribute points if he performs well enough. The evening event gives the player a choice of studying (a pop-up on the screen that gives the answer to a potential exam question), meeting with a tutor (a two-night event where one receives a five-question quiz to improve his GPA), participating in a position drill (a two-night event where the player takes part in one of his position's four specific drills from camp to earn attribute points), or participating in a campus social activity, which boosts popularity. Weekends are simulated except for the game, if there is one that weekend.\n\n== ''NCAA Football 07'' on the Xbox 360 ==\nThe Xbox 360 version of the game was thought by many to be incomplete as it lacked features of the console versions such as Campus Legend mode and Spring Drills. However, the game featured several mini-games of its own such as [[bowling]], where the player is put at the 20-yard line of the opponent's end zone and a touchdown is considered a [[Strike (bowling)|strike]] and if a touchdown scored on a second-down play is a [[spare (bowling)|spare]], as in bowling. Graphics in the game were well-done and showed great representation. Other problems with the game were offensive or created or edited players in the game imported to ''[[Madden NFL 07]]'' were un-signable at a rating of \"99\" and contracted at a high amount of money which were over the game's salary cap. Also, draft classes had defensive players as listed as top five picks and very few offensive players were top five or top ten picks in the NFL Draft. \"Create-a-player\" required the player to insert the player's name and gear, but the player's look or appearance could not be changed after the player was created. Also unlike ''Madden 07'' players ratings and names could be edited.\n\n==Awards & Reception==\nThe [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] version of the game is the most critically successful, receiving an 87.8% on GameRankings.\n\n===Awards===\n*Received [[IGN]]'s award for Best [[PlayStation 2|PS2]] Sports Game of 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestof.ign.com/2006/ps2/16.html |title=IGN.com Presents: the best of 2006 |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n*Gaming Target - \"52 Games We'll Still Be Playing From 2006\" selection <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamingtarget.com/article.php?artid=6371 |title=52 Games we'll still be playing from 2006 |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sports.ign.com/articles/703/703531p1.html Reggie Bush Immortalized]\n*[http://sports.ign.com/articles/702/702461p1.html NCAA Football 360: First Look]\n\n{{NCAA Football games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ncaa Football 07}}\n[[Category:2006 video games]]\n[[Category:College football video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Portable games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts games]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:North America-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:NCAA video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title=NCAA Football 07\n|image=NCAA Football 07 Coverart.jpg\n|developer=[[EA Tiburon]]\n|publisher=[[EA Sports]]\n|designer=\n|engine=\n|released=July 18, 2006\n|genre=[[Sports game|Sports]], [[American football]]\n|modes=[[single-player video game|Single player]], [[multiplayer video game|multiplayer]], multiplayer online\n|platforms=[[PlayStation 2|PS2]], [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]], [[Xbox 360]], [[PlayStation Portable|PSP]]\n}}\n\n'''''NCAA Football 07''''' is a [[college football|collegiate football]] [[video game]] published by [[Electronic Arts]]. It is the successor to ''[[NCAA Football 06]]'' in the ''[[NCAA Football series|NCAA Football]]'' series. The product features former [[University of Southern California|USC]] player [[Reggie Bush]] on the cover. While there weren't any new, major features added to the PlayStation 2 and Xbox games, tweaks were added to improve the existing features.\n\nThe theme for ''07'' is \"Turn the Tide\". Like [[NCAA Football 2005|the 2005 version]] said for home-field advantage, this year's version emphasizes that momentum is more important in college football than any other sport. This is illustrated by a momentum meter on the score graphic at the top (or bottom, in the case of the Xbox 360 version) of the screen. The more the meter is shifted towards a team, the better its players will perform (ex. If the momentum bar is all the way full with a +5 number below it (or above it), all players on the team will have their attributes boosted 5 points).\n\n''NCAA Football 07'' also includes spring drills, an update to Race for the Heisman mode called Campus Legend (which plays more like NFL Superstar mode in ''[[Madden NFL 07|Madden]]''), [[ESPN]] integration, and a spring game in Dynasty and Campus Legend modes. ESPN integration is expected to increase with the next NCAA Football releases.\n\n\n==Campus Legend==\n\nCampus Legend, for the most part, runs on the same system as its predecessor, Race for the Heisman. One creates a player, goes to a football camp, performs in drills, and is awarded a scholarship to play for a Division 1-A program. However, changes begin right from the start of camp. \n<sup>Campus Legend was not available on the Xbox 360 Version of the game.</sup>\n\n===Camp===\nRather than picking one drill to participate in, the player participates in a series of four drills which vary by position. (e.g. player gains attribute points - one to sixteen points depending on the performance - by repeatedly tapping A on the [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] during the 40 Yard Dash.)\n\n===Picking a school===\n\n[[Image:Ncaa 2007 screenshot.jpg|left|thumb|300px|Screenshot of in-game action between [[Virginia Tech]] and [[University of Virginia|Virginia]] at [[Lane Stadium]]]]\nAnother change in ''NCAA Football 07'' is which schools you can attend. Rather than choosing one of three scholarships or applying as a walk-on to another program, performance in camp determines your points and the distribution of those to your player will determine the caliber of your player (between one and five stars). This, in turn, determines how many of the 119 schools one can sign with and how highly those teams are ranked that you sign with. For example, a five-star recruit has the option to sign with any Division 1-A program of any rank and has a 50% popularity bonus, while a four-star recruit can sign with any Division 1-A program without the bonus. The lower the caliber, the fewer schools and lower rank one can choose from.\n\n===The Dorm===\nOnce moved into the dorm, a player is required to choose a major. While some are legitimate (e.g. chemistry, sports medicine, English), others are rather odd (e.g. [[ESPN]], 1-AA team nicknames, sports geography). Academic performance will improve a player's ratings, but one must choose a major that improves relevant ratings. For example, a quarterback would not want to major in something that would improve his tackling ability. In your dorm room, there is also a fan mailbox, where you can read generated mail from your fans. Also added is an NCAA progress report, where you can check your GPA, athletic goals, attribute point bonuses, and popularity; a computer to check rankings anywhere from the Heisman watch to All-Americans to the coaches' and AP polls; a closet to edit appearance, gear, and attribute points; and a school magazine chronicling headlines from your team (or, in case of a senior year, they will boast about the player).  The dorm room also featured a picture of the player's current girlfriend, with the beauty depending on the player's success; this feature was removed for the NCAA football 08 edition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/780/780221p1.html |title=NCAA Football 08 Preview |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n\n===During the year===\nCampus Legend introduces a challenge for the player to balance academic performance, athletic performance, and campus popularity in hopes of becoming the greatest to ever attend his school. Each weekday on the calendar in the dorm has a morning, afternoon, and evening event. The morning event is always classes (with the exception of the midterm and final exams), and is automatically simulated (unless it's an aforementioned test). The afternoon event is always practice, where one can earn attribute points if he performs well enough. The evening event gives the player a choice of studying (a pop-up on the screen that gives the answer to a potential exam question), meeting with a tutor (a two-night event where one receives a five-question quiz to improve his GPA), participating in a position drill (a two-night event where the player takes part in one of his position's four specific drills from camp to earn attribute points), or participating in a campus social activity, which boosts popularity. Weekends are simulated except for the game, if there is one that weekend.\n\n== ''NCAA Football 07'' on the Xbox 360 ==\nThe Xbox 360 version of the game was thought by many to be incomplete as it lacked features of the console versions such as Campus Legend mode and Spring Drills. However, the game featured several mini-games of its own such as [[bowling]], where the player is put at the 20-yard line of the opponent's end zone and a touchdown is considered a [[Strike (bowling)|strike]] and if a touchdown scored on a second-down play is a [[spare (bowling)|spare]], as in bowling. Graphics in the game were well-done and showed great representation. Other problems with the game were offensive or created or edited players in the game imported to ''[[Madden NFL 07]]'' were un-signable at a rating of \"99\" and contracted at a high amount of money which were over the game's salary cap. Also, draft classes had defensive players as listed as top five picks and very few offensive players were top five or top ten picks in the NFL Draft. \"Create-a-player\" required the player to insert the player's name and gear, but the player's look or appearance could not be changed after the player was created. Also unlike ''Madden 07'' players ratings and names could be edited.\n\n==Awards & Reception==\nThe [[Xbox (console)|Xbox]] version of the game is the most critically successful, receiving an 87.8% on GameRankings.\n\n===Awards===\n*Received [[IGN]]'s award for Best [[PlayStation 2|PS2]] Sports Game of 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bestof.ign.com/2006/ps2/16.html |title=IGN.com Presents: the best of 2006 |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n*Gaming Target - \"52 Games We'll Still Be Playing From 2006\" selection <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamingtarget.com/article.php?artid=6371 |title=52 Games we'll still be playing from 2006 |accessdate=2008-05-26 |publisher= |date= }}</ref>\n\n==Sources==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://sports.ign.com/articles/703/703531p1.html Reggie Bush Immortalized]\n*[http://sports.ign.com/articles/702/702461p1.html NCAA Football 360: First Look]\n\n{{NCAA Football games}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ncaa Football 07}}\n[[Category:2006 video games]]\n[[Category:College football video games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation Portable games]]\n[[Category:Xbox games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts games]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:North America-exclusive video games]]\n[[Category:Multiplayer and single-player video games]]\n[[Category:NCAA video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "2601:244:4e01:f211:85da:c830:be2:f6f1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200ePicking a school)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NCAA_Football_07"}
