{"title_page": "Paul Biya", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2nd President of Cameroon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Paul Biya\n|image         = Paul Biya 2014.png\n|office        = 2nd [[List of heads of state of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]]\n|primeminister = [[Bello Bouba Maigari]]<br />[[Luc Ayang]]<br />[[Sadou Hayatou]]<br />[[Simon Achidi Achu]]<br />[[Peter Mafany Musonge]]<br />[[Ephra\u00efm Inoni]]<br />[[Phil\u00e9mon Yang]]<br />[[Joseph Ngute]]\n|term_start= 6 November 1982\n|term_end=\n|predecessor   = [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = 1st [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]]\n|president1    = [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]\n|term_start1   = 30 June 1975\n|term_end1     = 6 November 1982\n|predecessor1  = Position established\n|successor1    = [[Bello Bouba Maigari]]\n|birth_name=Paul Barth\u00e9lemy Biya'a bi Mvondo\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1933|2|13|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Mvomeka'a]], [[French Cameroons]] {{small|(now [[Cameroon]])}}\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement|RDPC]]\n|spouse        = [[Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya]] {{small|(Before 1992)}}<br />[[Chantal Biya|Chantal Vigouroux]] {{small|(1994\u2013present)}}\n|alma_mater    = [[\u00c9cole nationale d'administration|National School of Administration, Paris]]<br />[[Sciences Po|Institute of Political Studies, Paris]]\n|religion      = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n[[File:Paul biya and colin powell.jpg|thumb|Biya and U.S. [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]]]]\n\n'''Paul Biya''' (born '''Paul Barth\u00e9lemy Biya'a bi Mvondo'''; 13 February 1933) is a [[Cameroon]]ian politician serving as the [[List of presidents of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]] since 6 November 1982.<ref name=Pres>[http://www.prc.cm/index_fr.php?link=6 Profile of Biya at Cameroonian presidency web site] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Elect>[http://www.presidential2004.gov.cm/candidats.php?id_cand=10&module=bio&lang=en Biography at 2004 presidential election web site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015452/http://www.presidential2004.gov.cm/candidats.php?id_cand=10&module=bio&lang=en |date=30 September 2007 }}.</ref>\n\nA native of Cameroon's south, Biya rose rapidly as a bureaucrat under President [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]] in the 1960s, serving as Secretary-General of the Presidency from 1968 to 1975 and then as [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]] from 1975 to 1982. He succeeded Ahidjo as president upon the latter's surprise resignation in 1982 and consolidated power in a 1983\u20131984 staged attempted coup{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} in which he eliminated all his rivals.\n\nHis regime is supported by France, which supplies it with weapons and trains its forces. France is the leading foreign investor, ahead of the United States. One hundred and five French subsidiaries are located in all key sectors (oil, timber, construction, mobile telephony, transport, banking, insurance, etc.).<ref name=modik />\n\nBiya introduced political reforms within the context of a [[One-party state|one-party system]] in the 1980s. Under serious pressure, he accepted the introduction of multiparty politics in the early 1990s. He won the contentious [[1992 Cameroonian presidential election|1992 presidential election]] with 40% of the plural, single-ballot vote and was re-elected by large margins in 1997, 2004, 2011 and 2018. Opposition politicians and Western governments have alleged voting irregularities and fraud on each of these occasions. Many independent sources have provided evidence that he did not win the elections in 1992, and that subsequent elections were rampant with fraud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cameroonvoice.com/news/article-news-8679.html|title=Elections. La fraude \"made in Cameroon\" fait fureur|website=www.cameroonvoice.com}}</ref>\n\nBiya is currently the longest-ruling non-royal leader in the world and the [[Lists of state leaders by age|oldest ruler in Africa]].\n\nBiya has maintained Cameroon's close relationship with [[France]], one of Cameroon's former [[French Cameroon|colonial ruler]]s besides the United Kingdom and Germany.\n\n==Personal life==\nPaul Biya was born in the village of [[Mvomeka'a]]<ref name=Pres/><ref name=Elect/> in the [[South Province, Cameroon|South Region]] of [[Cameroon]]. He studied at the Lyc\u00e9e General Leclerc, [[Yaound\u00e9]], and in France at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand]], [[Paris]], going on to the [[\u00c9cole Nationale de la France d'Outre-Mer|Institut des hautes \u00e9tudes d'Outre-Mer]], where he graduated in 1961 with a Higher Education Diploma in Public Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prc.cm/en/the-president/biography|title=Biography|website=www.prc.cm}}</ref> He married [[Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya]], who did not have any children, though she adopted Franck Biya who was born from a relationship of Paul Biya with another woman.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}} After Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya died on 29 July 1992, Paul Biya married [[Chantal Biya]] (37 years his junior) on 23 April 1994,<ref name=Elect/> and had two more children with her. Biya is a good friend of the former [[Angola]]n President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]].\n\n==Political career==\nAs an official in post-independence 1960s Cameroon, Biya rose to prominence under President [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]. After becoming Director of the Cabinet of the Minister of National Education in January 1964 and Secretary-General of the Ministry of National Education in July 1965, he was named Director of the Civil Cabinet of the President in December 1967 and Secretary-General of the Presidency (while remaining Director of the Civil Cabinet) in January 1968. He gained the rank of Minister in August 1968 and the rank of Minister of State in June 1970, while remaining Secretary-General of the Presidency. Following the creation of a [[unitary state]] in 1972, he became [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]] on 30 June 1975. In June 1979, a law designated the Prime Minister as the President's constitutional successor. Ahidjo unexpectedly announced his resignation on 4 November 1982, and Biya accordingly succeeded him as President of Cameroon on 6 November.<ref name=Pres/><ref name=Elect/>\n\nBecause Biya is a [[Christianity|Christian]] from the South Region of Cameroon, it was considered surprising that he was chosen by Ahidjo, a [[Islam|Muslim]] from the north, as his successor. His father who was a catechist wanted him to be in the clergy but at the age of 16 while in Catholic school, he was dismissed. After Biya became President, Ahidjo initially remained head of the ruling [[Cameroon National Union]] (CNU). Biya was brought into the CNU Central Committee and Political Bureau and was elected as the Vice-President of the CNU. On 11 December 1982, he was placed in charge of managing party affairs in Ahidjo's absence. During the first months after Biya's succession, he continued to show loyalty to Ahidjo, and Ahidjo continued to show support for Biya, but in 1983 a deep rift developed between the two. Ahidjo went into exile in France, and from there he publicly accused Biya of abuse of power and paranoia about plots against him. The two could not be reconciled despite efforts by several foreign leaders. After Ahidjo resigned as CNU leader, Biya took the helm of the party at an \"extraordinary session\" of the CNU party held on 14 September 1983.<ref name=KT>Milton H. Krieger and Joseph Takougang, ''African State and Society in the 1990s: Cameroon's Political Crossroads'' (2000), Westview Press, pages 65\u201374.</ref>\n\nIn November 1983, Biya announced that the next presidential election would be held on 14 January 1984; it had been previously scheduled for 1985. He was the sole candidate in this election and won 99.98% of the vote.<ref name=KT/> In February 1984, Ahidjo was put on trial ''in absentia'' for alleged involvement in a 1983 [[coup]] plot, along with two others; they were sentenced to death, although Biya commuted their sentences to life in prison, a gesture seen by many as a sign of weakness.<ref name=WP>Jonathan C. Randal, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/19/AR2006071901340_pf.html \"Tales of Ex-Leader's Role In Revolt Stun Cameroon\"], ''The Washington Post'', 15 April 1984, page A01.</ref> Biya survived a [[1984 Cameroonian coup attempt|military coup attempt]] on 6 April 1984, following his decision on the previous day to disband the Republican Guard and disperse its members across the military.<ref name=KT/> Estimates of the death toll ranged from 71 (according to the government)<ref name=\"WP\"/> to about 1,000.<ref name=KT/> Northern Muslims were the primary participants in this coup attempt, which was seen by many as an attempt to restore that group's supremacy; Biya, however, chose to emphasize national unity and did not focus blame on northern Muslims.<ref name=KT/><ref name=WP/> Ahidjo was widely believed to have orchestrated the coup attempt,<ref name=WP/> and Biya is thought to have learned of the plot in advance and to have disbanded the Republican Guard as a reaction, forcing the coup plotters to act earlier than they had planned, which may have been a crucial factor in the coup's failure.<ref name=KT/><ref name=WP/>\n\nIt shall adopt a structural adjustment plan submitted to it by the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) and [[World Bank]]: privatization, opening up to competition, reducing social spending, etc. Civil servants' salaries are reduced by 60%, the informal sector increased very significantly, but the ruling classes are not affected by this programme.<ref name=modik />>\n\nIn 1985, the CNU was transformed into the [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement]], in Bamenda the capital city of the Southern Cameroon and Biya was unlawfully elected as its president. He was also re-elected as President of Cameroon on 24 April 1988.<ref name=Elect/>\n\n[[File:Biya and Bush-2.jpg|thumb|Biya with U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] in 2003]]\nBiya initially took some steps to open up the regime, culminating in the decision to legalize opposition parties in 1990.  According to official results, Biya won the [[1992 Cameroonian presidential election|first multiparty presidential election]], held on 11 October 1992, with about 40% of the vote.  There was no provision for a runoff; the opposition was unable to unite around a single candidate.  The second placed candidate, [[John Fru Ndi]] of the opposition [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]] (SDF), officially received about 36%.<ref name=Mbaku>John Mukum Mbaku, \"Decolonization, Reunification and Federation in Cameroon\", in ''The Leadership Challenge in Africa: Cameroon Under Paul Biya'' (2004), ed. John Mukum Mbaku and Joseph Takougang, page 34.</ref><ref name=DB>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html Elections in Cameroon], African Elections Database.</ref> The results were strongly disputed by the opposition, which alleged fraud.<ref name=Mbaku/>\n\nIn the [[1997 Cameroonian presidential election|October 1997 presidential election]], which was boycotted by the main opposition parties, Biya was re-elected with 92.6 percent of the vote;<ref name=DB/><ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/home/RSDCOI/3c2b4e020.html \"UK Home Office Immigration and Nationality Directorate Country Assessment \u2013 Cameroon\"], UNHCR.org.</ref> he was sworn in on 3 November.<ref>[http://web.peacelink.it/africa/weekly/06_11_97 \"Cameroun. Biya reinstalle\"], ANB-BIA, 3 November 1997.</ref>\n\nBiya won another seven-year term in the [[2004 Cameroonian presidential election|11 October 2004 presidential election]], officially taking 70.92 percent of the vote,<ref name=Confirm>\"Cameroon's Supreme Court confirms Biya's re-election\" ''Agence France Presse'', 25 October 2004.</ref><ref name=Gov>[http://www.spm.gov.cm/detail_art.php?id_art=271&type=simpl&lang=en \"President Biya is sworn in for another seven-year mandate.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125004546/http://www.spm.gov.cm/detail_art.php?id_art=271&type=simpl&lang=en |date=25 November 2009 }}, Cameroonian government website].</ref> although the opposition alleged widespread fraud.<ref name=Confirm/> Biya was sworn in on 3 November.<ref name=Gov/>\n\nAfter being re-elected in 2004, Biya was barred by a two-term limit in the [[Constitution of Cameroon|1996 Constitution]] from running for President again in 2011, but he sought to revise this to allow him to run again. In his 2008 New Year's message, Biya expressed support for revising the Constitution, saying that it was undemocratic to limit the people's choice.<ref>[http://www.afriquenligne.fr/actualites/politique/cameroun%3a-paul-biya-va-modifier-la-constitution-2008010214343/ \"Cameroun: Paul Biya va modifier la Constitution\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305170820/http://www.afriquenligne.fr/actualites/politique/cameroun%3a-paul-biya-va-modifier-la-constitution-2008010214343/ |date=5 March 2013 }}, Panapress, 2 January 2008 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> The proposed removal of term limits was among the grievances expressed during [[2008 Cameroonian anti-government protests|violent protests]] in late February 2008. Nevertheless, on 10 April 2008, the National Assembly voted to change the Constitution to remove term limits. Given the RDPC's control of the National Assembly, the change was overwhelmingly approved, with 157 votes in favor and five opposed; the 15 deputies of the SDF chose to boycott the vote in protest. The change also provided for the President to enjoy immunity from prosecution for his actions as President after leaving office.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=44617 \"Cameroun: adoption d'une r\u00e9vision constitutionnelle controvers\u00e9e\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522000318/http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=44617 |date=22 May 2011 }}, AFP, 10 April 2008 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n[[File:Paul Biya with Obamas 2014.jpg|thumb|Biya with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in 2014]]\n\nHe has been consistently re-elected as the National President of the RDPC; he was re-elected at the party's second extraordinary congress on 7 July 2001 and its third extraordinary congress on 21 July 2006.<ref>[http://www.camerounlink.net/fr/news.php?nid=24113&kat=1&seite=195 \"21 ANS DE T\u00c2TONNEMENT\"], Camerounlink.net, 21 July 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/079/article_45203.asp \"Paul Biya r\u00e9\u00e9lu sans surprise \u00e0 la t\u00eate du RDPC\"], rfi.fr, 22 July 2006 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2006 he signed the [[Greentree Agreement]] with Nigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] which formally put an end to the [[Bakassi]] peninsula border dispute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2008/sgsm11745.doc.htm|title=AGREEMENT TRANSFERRING AUTHORITY OVER BAKASSI PENINSULA FROM NIGERIA TO CAMEROON \u2018TRIUMPH FOR THE RULE OF LAW\u2019, SECRETARY-GENERAL SAYS IN MESSAGE FOR CEREMONY - Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|website=www.un.org}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, riots broke out, calling for lower prices and the departure of Paul Biya. The demonstrators were severely repressed with reports of a hundred dead and thousands of arrests.<ref name=modik>Thomas Deltombe, Manuel Domergue, Jacob Tatsita, Kamerun !, La D\u00e9couverte, 2019</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Cameroonian presidential election|October 2011 presidential election]], Biya secured a sixth term in office, polling 77.9% of votes cast. [[John Fru Ndi]] was his nearest rival, polling 10%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameroonian president wins vote, extending 29-year-rule|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/22/world/africa/cameroon-election-outcome/|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=CNN|date=22 October 2010}}</ref> Biya's opponents alleged wide-scale fraud in the election and procedural irregularities were noted by the French and US governments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court declares Cameroon\u2019s Biya landslide poll winner, despite accusations of fraud|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/court-declares-cameroons-biya-landslide-poll-winner-despite-accusations-of-fraud/2011/10/21/gIQAhpjD4L_story.html|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=Washington Post|date=21 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=reuters>{{cite news|title=Cameroon's Biya promises youth jobs after poll win|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/cameroonNews/idAFL5E7LP4KO20111025|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 October 2011}}</ref> In his victory speech, Biya promised to stimulate growth and create jobs with a programme of public works which would \"transform our country into a vast construction site\".<ref name=reuters/> On 3 November 2011, he was sworn in for another term as President\n<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameroon: Biya sworn in for sixth presidential term\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15574922|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=BBC News |date=3 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nBiya won the 2018 presidential election with 71.3% of the vote.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/world/africa/cameroon-paul-biya-gets-seventh-term/index.html?no-st=9999999999 Cameroon's Paul Biya wins seventh term in office]</ref> The election was marred by violence and low voter turnout.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45940414 Cameroon's President Paul Biya wins seventh term]</ref>\n\n==Opposition and criticism==\n{{see|Human rights in Cameroon}}\nBiya is sometimes characterized as aloof, making relatively few public appearances. Since the early 1990s, he has faced his strongest opposition from the [[English-speaking world|Anglophone]] population of the former [[Southern Cameroons]] in the western part of the country.\n\nAlthough Biya made some efforts to open up the political environment, his regime still retains clear [[authoritarianism|authoritarian characteristics]] and has largely bucked the trend toward democracy in Africa since the 1990s.  Under the constitution, Biya has sweeping executive and legislative powers.  He even has considerable authority over the judiciary; the courts can only review a law's constitutionality at his request.  The RDPC continues to dominate the National Assembly, which does little more than approve his policies.\n\n\"Tyrants, the World's 20 Worst Living Dictators\", by [[David Wallechinsky]], ranked Biya with three others commonly in sub-Saharan Africa: [[Robert Mugabe]] of [[Zimbabwe]], [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo]] of [[Equatorial Guinea]], and [[Mswati III|King Mswati]] of [[Swaziland]]. He describes Cameroon's electoral process in these terms: \"Every few years, Biya stages an election to justify his continuing reign, but these elections have no credibility. In fact, Biya is credited with a creative innovation in the world of phony elections. In 2004, annoyed by the criticisms of international vote-monitoring groups, he paid for his own set of international observers, six ex-U.S. congressmen, who certified his election as free and fair.\"<ref>David Wallechinsky, \"Tyrants: the World's 20 Worst Living Dictators\", Regan Press, 2006, pp. 286\u2013290</ref> In a 2005 interview [[William Quantrill (diplomat)|William Quantrill]], a retired member of [[HM Diplomatic Service]], argued that the reluctance of Biya to delegate responsibility seriously hampered the quality of governance, with trivial decisions often delayed until he got round to delivering them, and that there was too much government interference in the economy in general.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kometa |first1=Georgiana Magho |title=There Was Disparity Between Biya's Professed Policies And Reality -Former British Ambassador |url=https://www.postnewsline.com/2005/06/strongthere_was.html |website=Up Station Mountain Club |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nBiya regularly spends extended periods of time in [[Switzerland]] at the Hotel [[InterContinental]] [[Geneva]] where the former director Herbert Schott reportedly said he comes to work without being disturbed.<ref>Jean Francis Belibi {{cite web |url=http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710300790.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110629144705/http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710300790.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2011 |title=Cameroun: Herbert Schott \u2013 Paul Biya est un sacr\u00e9 personnage |access-date=1 September 2016}}. fr.allafrica.com. 30 October 2007 (in French)</ref> These extended stays away from Cameroon \u2013 while sometimes as short as two weeks \u2013 are sometimes as long as three months and are almost always referred to as \"short stays\" in the state-owned press and other media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prc.cm/index_fr.php?link=magazine/sejour_prive_europe_310507 |title=Le Chef de l\u2019Etat en s\u00e9jour priv\u00e9 en Europe |publisher=Prc.cm |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prc.cm/index_en.php?link=magazine/retour_sejour_prive_europe_190607 |title=Le Pr\u00e9sident est de retour |language=French|publisher=Prc.cm |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref> In February 2008, he passed a bill that allows for having an additional term in office as president which was followed by civil unrests throughout the country. The main violent riots took place in the Western, English-speaking part of the country starting with a \"strike\" initiated by taxi drivers in Douala, allegedly causing more than 200 casualties in the end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freitag.de/2008/27/08270301.php |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804091315/http://www.freitag.de/2008/27/08270301.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 August 2012 |title=Anatomie eines Aufstandes: Dunkle Krawalle \u2013 Der Freitag |language=de |publisher=Freitag.de |accessdate=6 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/report/dissent-violently-repressed-cameroon-20090129 |title=Dissent violently repressed in Cameroon |accessdate=2010-12-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317052250/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/report/dissent-violently-repressed-cameroon-20090129 |archivedate=17 March 2011 |df=dmy }}. amnesty.org. 29 January 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://report2009.amnesty.org/en/regions/africa/cameroon |title=Cameroon &#124; Amnesty International Report 2009 |publisher=Report2009.amnesty.org |accessdate=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008000900/http://report2009.amnesty.org/en/regions/africa/cameroon |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2009, his holiday in France allegedly cost $40,000 a day spent on 43 hotel rooms.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8236962.stm \"Cameroon defends Biya hotel bills\"], BBC, 3 September 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Biya was ranked 19th in ''[[Parade Magazine]]'s'' Top 20 list of \"The World's Worst Dictators\".<ref>[http://www.parade.com/dictators/ The World's Worst Dictators]. Parade.com (2011-10-20). Retrieved on 2011-11-08.</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, [[Bertrand Teyou]] published a book titled ''La belle de la r\u00e9publique banani\u00e8re: Chantal Biya, de la rue au palais'' (English: \"''The beauty of the banana republic: Chantal Biya, from the streets to the palace''\"), tracing Chantal Biya's rise from humble origins to become Paul Biya's First Lady.<ref name=\"PEN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.penusa.org/ran-1211 |title=CAMEROON: Author jailed for insulting President's wife |date=25 March 2011 |publisher=[[International PEN]] |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> He was subsequently given a two-year prison term on charges of \"insult to character\" and organizing an \"illegal demonstration\" for attempting to hold a public reading.<ref name=\"PEN\" /> [[Amnesty International]] and [[International PEN]]'s Writers in Prison Committee both protested his arrest and issued appeals on his behalf; Amnesty International also named him a [[prisoner of conscience]].<ref name=\"PEN\" /><ref name=\"AI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/afr17/001/2011/en/ |title=Urgent Action:CAMEROONIAN WRITER HELD IN HARSH CONDITIONS |date=12 April 2011 |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |accessdate=21 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> He was freed on 2 May 2011 when the London chapter of International PEN agreed to pay his fine in order that he might seek treatment for his worsening health condition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camerpress.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=543:cameroun-lecrivain-bertrand-teyou-sort-de-prison&catid=67:politique&Itemid=66 |title=Cameroun: L'\u00e9crivain Bertrand Teyou Sort De Prison |date=2 May 2011 |publisher=camerpress.net |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, French citizen [[Michel Thierry Atangana]] was released from a makeshift [[Yaound\u00e9]] prison where, under Biya's orders, he had been arbitrarily detained for 17 years under false claims of embezzlement because of supposed closeness to presidential candidate [[Titus Edzoa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Michel-Thierry-Atangana-le-citoyen-oublie-850735|title=Fran\u00e7ais emprisonn\u00e9 17 ans au Cameroun - Michel Thierry Atangana, le citoyen oubli\u00e9|first=Paris|last=Match|publisher=}}</ref> Considered a [[political prisoner]] and [[prisoner of conscience]] by the [[United States Department of State]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Freedom House]], and the U.N. [[Working Group on Arbitrary Detention]] since 2005,<ref>http://www.cameroon-info.net/stories/0,39574,@,cameroun-selon-amnesty-international-michel-atangana-prisonnier-d-opinion.html {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322034501/http://www.cameroon-info.net/stories/0%2C39574%2C%40%2Ccameroun-selon-amnesty-international-michel-atangana-prisonnier-d-opinion.html |date=22 March 2016 }}</ref> Michel was released under Biya's personal decree but the Working Group's tripartite demands remain unfulfilled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/wgad/38-2013.html|title=University of Minnesota Human Rights Library|website=www1.umn.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/273095/societe/michel-thierry-atangana-dois-etre-rehabilite-reprendre-cours-de-vie/|title=Michel Thierry Atangana : \" Je dois \u00eatre r\u00e9habilit\u00e9 pour reprendre le cours de ma vie \" \u2013 JeuneAfrique.com|date=21 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Cameroonians in the nation's capital city of Yaound\u00e9 criticized Biya's reaction to the country's worst train crash in which 79 people died. Criticism included government officials who remained anonymous, fearing a backlash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/818654/cameroons-paul-biya-is-slammed-by-his-country-for-his-lukeware-reaction-to-the-eseka-train-crash/|title=Cameroonians are furious with their \u2018absent\u2019 president after a national tragedy|work=Quartz|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Anglophone protests in late 2016 were led by English-speaking lawyers in protest against the use of French in Cameroonian courts, which led to violent clashes with police. Opposition party leader Edna Njilin of the Cameroon People's Party spoke out against the enforced use of French in the classroom. In January 2017, the government ordered a suspension of Internet services in the Northwest and Southwest provinces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/02/03/africa/internet-shutdown-cameroon/index.html|title=Cameroon goes offline after Anglophone revolt|website=CNN|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref>  Criticism of the suspension and increased opposition led to resumption of services in late April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39665244|title=Cameroon ends internet shutdown on orders of President Paul Biya|date=2017-04-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2017, protests in Cameroon's English-speaking provinces and cities led to police responding with force, with 4 protesters killed and over 100 arrested. International criticism has been levied at the United States for their lack of response to the growing Cameroonian crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/06/02/cameroon-has-been-in-crisis-for-six-months-heres-what-you-need-to-know/|title=Analysis {{!}} Cameroon has been in crisis for six months. Here\u2019s what you need to know.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, a Cameroonian journalist working for [[Radio France Internationale]], [[Ahmed Abba]], was sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment by a military tribunal for failing to report acts of terrorism. The judgement was severely criticized by human rights groups including Amnesty International.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-for-ten-years-under-anti-terrorism-law/3824341.html|title=Cameroon Journalist Jailed for 10 Years Under Anti-terrorism Law|last=Reuters|work=VOA|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 November 2018, another Cameroonian journalist, Mimi Mefo, was arrested after reporting on social media that the Cameroonian military was behind the murder of an American missionary in the country, Charles Trumann, in October of that year.  Mefo was charged with \"publishing and propagating information that infringes on the territorial integrity of the Republic of Cameroon,\" but was released and charges were dropped on 12 November after her arrest was condemned by both local and international media groups.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-46194532|title=Cameroon drops fake news charges against Mimi Mefo|last=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Southern Cameroon ===\n\nIn early 2017, videos and reports surfaced online showing a genocide was taking place in Southern Cameroon,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cameroonconcordnews.com/crimes-against-humanity-and-genocide-in-southern-cameroons-mechanisms-for-redress/|title=Crimes against humanity and genocide in Southern Cameroons: Mechanisms for redress \u2013 Cameroon Concord News|website=www.cameroonconcordnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref> sanctioned and led by Paul Biya. A petition to the United Nations gave details of police raping students at a university.  Supporters are calling for the independence of Southern Cameroon before the violence escalates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribuneonlineng.com/southern-cameroonians-agitate-independence-republic-cameroon/|title=Southern Cameroonians agitate for independence from Republic of Cameroon - Tribune|date=2017-05-26|work=Tribune|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-GB}}</ref> The National Commission for Human Rights and Freedoms embarked on a fact-finding mission in [[Buea]] to investigate allegations of human rights abuses in the region.\n\nMany allegations of indiscriminate killing, burning of villages, rape and humiliation of English-speaking citizens carried out by the BIR (Bataillon d'Intervention Rapide) have been made along with supporting video footage. The BIR is a special force body that reports directly to President Biya. Individual sources testify that all of those sent to fight the secessionist militia are French speaking, thus widening the linguistic division between local residents. [https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-africa-44584122/witnessing-cameroon-s-descent-towards-civil-war][https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Paul Biya}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.prc.cm/en/}}\n*[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Cameroon.html World Statesmen \u2013 Cameroon]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Simon Pierre Tchoungui]]|as=Prime Minister of East Cameroon}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[Prime Minister of Cameroon]]|years=1975\u20131982}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Bello Bouba Maigari]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Salomon Tandeng Muna]]|as=Prime Minister of West Cameroon}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of state of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]]|years=1982\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CameroonPresidents}}\n{{CameroonPMs}}\n{{African Union chairpersons}}\n{{Commonwealth heads of government}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biya, Paul}}\n[[Category:1933 births|Biya, Paul]]\n[[Category:Cameroon People's Democratic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from South Region (Cameroon)]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Order of Chad]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ouissam Alaouite]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|2nd President of Cameroon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Paul Biya\n|image         = Paul Biya 2014.png\n|office        = 2nd [[List of heads of state of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]]\n|primeminister = [[Bello Bouba Maigari]]<br />[[Luc Ayang]]<br />[[Sadou Hayatou]]<br />[[Simon Achidi Achu]]<br />[[Peter Mafany Musonge]]<br />[[Ephra\u00efm Inoni]]<br />[[Phil\u00e9mon Yang]]<br />[[Joseph Ngute]]\n|term_start= 6 November 1982\n|term_end=\n|predecessor   = [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = 1st [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]]\n|president1    = [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]\n|term_start1   = 30 June 1975\n|term_end1     = 6 November 1982\n|predecessor1  = Position established\n|successor1    = [[Bello Bouba Maigari]]\n|birth_name=Paul Barth\u00e9lemy Biya'a bi Mvondo\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1933|2|13|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Mvomeka'a]], [[French Cameroons]] {{small|(now [[Cameroon]])}}\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement|RDPC]]\n|spouse        = [[Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya]] {{small|(Before 1992)}}<br />[[Chantal Biya|Chantal Vigouroux]] {{small|(1994\u2013present)}}\n|alma_mater    = [[\u00c9cole nationale d'administration|National School of Administration, Paris]]<br />[[Sciences Po|Institute of Political Studies, Paris]]\n|religion      = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n}}\n[[File:Paul biya and colin powell.jpg|thumb|Biya and U.S. [[United States Secretary of State|Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]]]]\n\n'''Paul Biya''' (born '''Paul Barth\u00e9lemy Biya'a bi Mvondo'''; 13 February 1933) is a [[Cameroon]]ian politician serving as the [[List of presidents of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]] since 6 November 1982.<ref name=Pres>[http://www.prc.cm/index_fr.php?link=6 Profile of Biya at Cameroonian presidency web site] {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref name=Elect>[http://www.presidential2004.gov.cm/candidats.php?id_cand=10&module=bio&lang=en Biography at 2004 presidential election web site] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930015452/http://www.presidential2004.gov.cm/candidats.php?id_cand=10&module=bio&lang=en |date=30 September 2007 }}.</ref>\n\nA native of Cameroon's south, Biya rose rapidly as a bureaucrat under President [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]] in the 1960s, serving as Secretary-General of the Presidency from 1968 to 1975 and then as [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]] from 1975 to 1982. He succeeded Ahidjo as president upon the latter's surprise resignation in 1982 and consolidated power in a 1983\u20131984 staged attempted coup{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} in which he eliminated all his rivals.\n\nIts regime is supported by France, which supplies it with weapons and trains its forces. France is the leading foreign investor, ahead of the United States. One hundred and five French subsidiaries are located in all key sectors (oil, timber, construction, mobile telephony, transport, banking, insurance, etc.).<ref name=modik />\n\nBiya introduced political reforms within the context of a [[One-party state|one-party system]] in the 1980s. Under serious pressure, he accepted the introduction of multiparty politics in the early 1990s. He won the contentious [[1992 Cameroonian presidential election|1992 presidential election]] with 40% of the plural, single-ballot vote and was re-elected by large margins in 1997, 2004, 2011 and 2018. Opposition politicians and Western governments have alleged voting irregularities and fraud on each of these occasions. Many independent sources have provided evidence that he did not win the elections in 1992, and that subsequent elections were rampant with fraud.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cameroonvoice.com/news/article-news-8679.html|title=Elections. La fraude \"made in Cameroon\" fait fureur|website=www.cameroonvoice.com}}</ref>\n\nBiya is currently the longest-ruling non-royal leader in the world and the [[Lists of state leaders by age|oldest ruler in Africa]].\n\nBiya has maintained Cameroon's close relationship with [[France]], one of Cameroon's former [[French Cameroon|colonial ruler]]s besides the United Kingdom and Germany.\n\n==Personal life==\nPaul Biya was born in the village of [[Mvomeka'a]]<ref name=Pres/><ref name=Elect/> in the [[South Province, Cameroon|South Region]] of [[Cameroon]]. He studied at the Lyc\u00e9e General Leclerc, [[Yaound\u00e9]], and in France at the [[Lyc\u00e9e Louis-le-Grand]], [[Paris]], going on to the [[\u00c9cole Nationale de la France d'Outre-Mer|Institut des hautes \u00e9tudes d'Outre-Mer]], where he graduated in 1961 with a Higher Education Diploma in Public Law.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prc.cm/en/the-president/biography|title=Biography|website=www.prc.cm}}</ref> He married [[Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya]], who did not have any children, though she adopted Franck Biya who was born from a relationship of Paul Biya with another woman.{{Citation needed|date=July 2009}} After Jeanne-Ir\u00e8ne Biya died on 29 July 1992, Paul Biya married [[Chantal Biya]] (37 years his junior) on 23 April 1994,<ref name=Elect/> and had two more children with her. Biya is a good friend of the former [[Angola]]n President [[Jos\u00e9 Eduardo dos Santos]].\n\n==Political career==\nAs an official in post-independence 1960s Cameroon, Biya rose to prominence under President [[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]. After becoming Director of the Cabinet of the Minister of National Education in January 1964 and Secretary-General of the Ministry of National Education in July 1965, he was named Director of the Civil Cabinet of the President in December 1967 and Secretary-General of the Presidency (while remaining Director of the Civil Cabinet) in January 1968. He gained the rank of Minister in August 1968 and the rank of Minister of State in June 1970, while remaining Secretary-General of the Presidency. Following the creation of a [[unitary state]] in 1972, he became [[Prime Minister of Cameroon]] on 30 June 1975. In June 1979, a law designated the Prime Minister as the President's constitutional successor. Ahidjo unexpectedly announced his resignation on 4 November 1982, and Biya accordingly succeeded him as President of Cameroon on 6 November.<ref name=Pres/><ref name=Elect/>\n\nBecause Biya is a [[Christianity|Christian]] from the South Region of Cameroon, it was considered surprising that he was chosen by Ahidjo, a [[Islam|Muslim]] from the north, as his successor. His father who was a catechist wanted him to be in the clergy but at the age of 16 while in Catholic school, he was dismissed. After Biya became President, Ahidjo initially remained head of the ruling [[Cameroon National Union]] (CNU). Biya was brought into the CNU Central Committee and Political Bureau and was elected as the Vice-President of the CNU. On 11 December 1982, he was placed in charge of managing party affairs in Ahidjo's absence. During the first months after Biya's succession, he continued to show loyalty to Ahidjo, and Ahidjo continued to show support for Biya, but in 1983 a deep rift developed between the two. Ahidjo went into exile in France, and from there he publicly accused Biya of abuse of power and paranoia about plots against him. The two could not be reconciled despite efforts by several foreign leaders. After Ahidjo resigned as CNU leader, Biya took the helm of the party at an \"extraordinary session\" of the CNU party held on 14 September 1983.<ref name=KT>Milton H. Krieger and Joseph Takougang, ''African State and Society in the 1990s: Cameroon's Political Crossroads'' (2000), Westview Press, pages 65\u201374.</ref>\n\nIn November 1983, Biya announced that the next presidential election would be held on 14 January 1984; it had been previously scheduled for 1985. He was the sole candidate in this election and won 99.98% of the vote.<ref name=KT/> In February 1984, Ahidjo was put on trial ''in absentia'' for alleged involvement in a 1983 [[coup]] plot, along with two others; they were sentenced to death, although Biya commuted their sentences to life in prison, a gesture seen by many as a sign of weakness.<ref name=WP>Jonathan C. Randal, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/07/19/AR2006071901340_pf.html \"Tales of Ex-Leader's Role In Revolt Stun Cameroon\"], ''The Washington Post'', 15 April 1984, page A01.</ref> Biya survived a [[1984 Cameroonian coup attempt|military coup attempt]] on 6 April 1984, following his decision on the previous day to disband the Republican Guard and disperse its members across the military.<ref name=KT/> Estimates of the death toll ranged from 71 (according to the government)<ref name=\"WP\"/> to about 1,000.<ref name=KT/> Northern Muslims were the primary participants in this coup attempt, which was seen by many as an attempt to restore that group's supremacy; Biya, however, chose to emphasize national unity and did not focus blame on northern Muslims.<ref name=KT/><ref name=WP/> Ahidjo was widely believed to have orchestrated the coup attempt,<ref name=WP/> and Biya is thought to have learned of the plot in advance and to have disbanded the Republican Guard as a reaction, forcing the coup plotters to act earlier than they had planned, which may have been a crucial factor in the coup's failure.<ref name=KT/><ref name=WP/>\n\nIt shall adopt a structural adjustment plan submitted to it by the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) and [[World Bank]]: privatization, opening up to competition, reducing social spending, etc. Civil servants' salaries are reduced by 60%, the informal sector increased very significantly, but the ruling classes are not affected by this programme.<ref name=modik />>\n\nIn 1985, the CNU was transformed into the [[Cameroon People's Democratic Movement]], in Bamenda the capital city of the Southern Cameroon and Biya was unlawfully elected as its president. He was also re-elected as President of Cameroon on 24 April 1988.<ref name=Elect/>\n\n[[File:Biya and Bush-2.jpg|thumb|Biya with U.S. President [[George W. Bush]] in 2003]]\nBiya initially took some steps to open up the regime, culminating in the decision to legalize opposition parties in 1990.  According to official results, Biya won the [[1992 Cameroonian presidential election|first multiparty presidential election]], held on 11 October 1992, with about 40% of the vote.  There was no provision for a runoff; the opposition was unable to unite around a single candidate.  The second placed candidate, [[John Fru Ndi]] of the opposition [[Social Democratic Front (Cameroon)|Social Democratic Front]] (SDF), officially received about 36%.<ref name=Mbaku>John Mukum Mbaku, \"Decolonization, Reunification and Federation in Cameroon\", in ''The Leadership Challenge in Africa: Cameroon Under Paul Biya'' (2004), ed. John Mukum Mbaku and Joseph Takougang, page 34.</ref><ref name=DB>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/cm.html Elections in Cameroon], African Elections Database.</ref> The results were strongly disputed by the opposition, which alleged fraud.<ref name=Mbaku/>\n\nIn the [[1997 Cameroonian presidential election|October 1997 presidential election]], which was boycotted by the main opposition parties, Biya was re-elected with 92.6 percent of the vote;<ref name=DB/><ref>[http://www.unhcr.org/home/RSDCOI/3c2b4e020.html \"UK Home Office Immigration and Nationality Directorate Country Assessment \u2013 Cameroon\"], UNHCR.org.</ref> he was sworn in on 3 November.<ref>[http://web.peacelink.it/africa/weekly/06_11_97 \"Cameroun. Biya reinstalle\"], ANB-BIA, 3 November 1997.</ref>\n\nBiya won another seven-year term in the [[2004 Cameroonian presidential election|11 October 2004 presidential election]], officially taking 70.92 percent of the vote,<ref name=Confirm>\"Cameroon's Supreme Court confirms Biya's re-election\" ''Agence France Presse'', 25 October 2004.</ref><ref name=Gov>[http://www.spm.gov.cm/detail_art.php?id_art=271&type=simpl&lang=en \"President Biya is sworn in for another seven-year mandate.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091125004546/http://www.spm.gov.cm/detail_art.php?id_art=271&type=simpl&lang=en |date=25 November 2009 }}, Cameroonian government website].</ref> although the opposition alleged widespread fraud.<ref name=Confirm/> Biya was sworn in on 3 November.<ref name=Gov/>\n\nAfter being re-elected in 2004, Biya was barred by a two-term limit in the [[Constitution of Cameroon|1996 Constitution]] from running for President again in 2011, but he sought to revise this to allow him to run again. In his 2008 New Year's message, Biya expressed support for revising the Constitution, saying that it was undemocratic to limit the people's choice.<ref>[http://www.afriquenligne.fr/actualites/politique/cameroun%3a-paul-biya-va-modifier-la-constitution-2008010214343/ \"Cameroun: Paul Biya va modifier la Constitution\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130305170820/http://www.afriquenligne.fr/actualites/politique/cameroun%3a-paul-biya-va-modifier-la-constitution-2008010214343/ |date=5 March 2013 }}, Panapress, 2 January 2008 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref> The proposed removal of term limits was among the grievances expressed during [[2008 Cameroonian anti-government protests|violent protests]] in late February 2008. Nevertheless, on 10 April 2008, the National Assembly voted to change the Constitution to remove term limits. Given the RDPC's control of the National Assembly, the change was overwhelmingly approved, with 157 votes in favor and five opposed; the 15 deputies of the SDF chose to boycott the vote in protest. The change also provided for the President to enjoy immunity from prosecution for his actions as President after leaving office.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=44617 \"Cameroun: adoption d'une r\u00e9vision constitutionnelle controvers\u00e9e\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522000318/http://www.jeuneafrique.com/fluxafp/fil_info.asp?art_cle=44617 |date=22 May 2011 }}, AFP, 10 April 2008 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n[[File:Paul Biya with Obamas 2014.jpg|thumb|Biya with U.S. President [[Barack Obama]] in 2014]]\n\nHe has been consistently re-elected as the National President of the RDPC; he was re-elected at the party's second extraordinary congress on 7 July 2001 and its third extraordinary congress on 21 July 2006.<ref>[http://www.camerounlink.net/fr/news.php?nid=24113&kat=1&seite=195 \"21 ANS DE T\u00c2TONNEMENT\"], Camerounlink.net, 21 July 2007 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref><ref>[http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/079/article_45203.asp \"Paul Biya r\u00e9\u00e9lu sans surprise \u00e0 la t\u00eate du RDPC\"], rfi.fr, 22 July 2006 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nOn 12 June 2006 he signed the [[Greentree Agreement]] with Nigerian President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]] which formally put an end to the [[Bakassi]] peninsula border dispute.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/News/Press/docs/2008/sgsm11745.doc.htm|title=AGREEMENT TRANSFERRING AUTHORITY OVER BAKASSI PENINSULA FROM NIGERIA TO CAMEROON \u2018TRIUMPH FOR THE RULE OF LAW\u2019, SECRETARY-GENERAL SAYS IN MESSAGE FOR CEREMONY - Meetings Coverage and Press Releases|website=www.un.org}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2008, riots broke out, calling for lower prices and the departure of Paul Biya. The demonstrators were severely repressed with reports of a hundred dead and thousands of arrests.<ref name=modik>Thomas Deltombe, Manuel Domergue, Jacob Tatsita, Kamerun !, La D\u00e9couverte, 2019</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Cameroonian presidential election|October 2011 presidential election]], Biya secured a sixth term in office, polling 77.9% of votes cast. [[John Fru Ndi]] was his nearest rival, polling 10%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameroonian president wins vote, extending 29-year-rule|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/10/22/world/africa/cameroon-election-outcome/|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=CNN|date=22 October 2010}}</ref> Biya's opponents alleged wide-scale fraud in the election and procedural irregularities were noted by the French and US governments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court declares Cameroon\u2019s Biya landslide poll winner, despite accusations of fraud|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/court-declares-cameroons-biya-landslide-poll-winner-despite-accusations-of-fraud/2011/10/21/gIQAhpjD4L_story.html|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=Washington Post|date=21 October 2011}}</ref><ref name=reuters>{{cite news|title=Cameroon's Biya promises youth jobs after poll win|url=https://af.reuters.com/article/cameroonNews/idAFL5E7LP4KO20111025|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 October 2011}}</ref> In his victory speech, Biya promised to stimulate growth and create jobs with a programme of public works which would \"transform our country into a vast construction site\".<ref name=reuters/> On 3 November 2011, he was sworn in for another term as President\n<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameroon: Biya sworn in for sixth presidential term\n|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15574922|accessdate=4 November 2011|newspaper=BBC News |date=3 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nBiya won the 2018 presidential election with 71.3% of the vote.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/22/world/africa/cameroon-paul-biya-gets-seventh-term/index.html?no-st=9999999999 Cameroon's Paul Biya wins seventh term in office]</ref> The election was marred by violence and low voter turnout.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-45940414 Cameroon's President Paul Biya wins seventh term]</ref>\n\n==Opposition and criticism==\n{{see|Human rights in Cameroon}}\nBiya is sometimes characterized as aloof, making relatively few public appearances. Since the early 1990s, he has faced his strongest opposition from the [[English-speaking world|Anglophone]] population of the former [[Southern Cameroons]] in the western part of the country.\n\nAlthough Biya made some efforts to open up the political environment, his regime still retains clear [[authoritarianism|authoritarian characteristics]] and has largely bucked the trend toward democracy in Africa since the 1990s.  Under the constitution, Biya has sweeping executive and legislative powers.  He even has considerable authority over the judiciary; the courts can only review a law's constitutionality at his request.  The RDPC continues to dominate the National Assembly, which does little more than approve his policies.\n\n\"Tyrants, the World's 20 Worst Living Dictators\", by [[David Wallechinsky]], ranked Biya with three others commonly in sub-Saharan Africa: [[Robert Mugabe]] of [[Zimbabwe]], [[Teodoro Obiang Nguema Mbasogo]] of [[Equatorial Guinea]], and [[Mswati III|King Mswati]] of [[Swaziland]]. He describes Cameroon's electoral process in these terms: \"Every few years, Biya stages an election to justify his continuing reign, but these elections have no credibility. In fact, Biya is credited with a creative innovation in the world of phony elections. In 2004, annoyed by the criticisms of international vote-monitoring groups, he paid for his own set of international observers, six ex-U.S. congressmen, who certified his election as free and fair.\"<ref>David Wallechinsky, \"Tyrants: the World's 20 Worst Living Dictators\", Regan Press, 2006, pp. 286\u2013290</ref> In a 2005 interview [[William Quantrill (diplomat)|William Quantrill]], a retired member of [[HM Diplomatic Service]], argued that the reluctance of Biya to delegate responsibility seriously hampered the quality of governance, with trivial decisions often delayed until he got round to delivering them, and that there was too much government interference in the economy in general.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kometa |first1=Georgiana Magho |title=There Was Disparity Between Biya's Professed Policies And Reality -Former British Ambassador |url=https://www.postnewsline.com/2005/06/strongthere_was.html |website=Up Station Mountain Club |accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nBiya regularly spends extended periods of time in [[Switzerland]] at the Hotel [[InterContinental]] [[Geneva]] where the former director Herbert Schott reportedly said he comes to work without being disturbed.<ref>Jean Francis Belibi {{cite web |url=http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710300790.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110629144705/http://fr.allafrica.com/stories/200710300790.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=29 June 2011 |title=Cameroun: Herbert Schott \u2013 Paul Biya est un sacr\u00e9 personnage |access-date=1 September 2016}}. fr.allafrica.com. 30 October 2007 (in French)</ref> These extended stays away from Cameroon \u2013 while sometimes as short as two weeks \u2013 are sometimes as long as three months and are almost always referred to as \"short stays\" in the state-owned press and other media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prc.cm/index_fr.php?link=magazine/sejour_prive_europe_310507 |title=Le Chef de l\u2019Etat en s\u00e9jour priv\u00e9 en Europe |publisher=Prc.cm |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prc.cm/index_en.php?link=magazine/retour_sejour_prive_europe_190607 |title=Le Pr\u00e9sident est de retour |language=French|publisher=Prc.cm |accessdate=6 November 2011}}</ref> In February 2008, he passed a bill that allows for having an additional term in office as president which was followed by civil unrests throughout the country. The main violent riots took place in the Western, English-speaking part of the country starting with a \"strike\" initiated by taxi drivers in Douala, allegedly causing more than 200 casualties in the end.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freitag.de/2008/27/08270301.php |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120804091315/http://www.freitag.de/2008/27/08270301.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=4 August 2012 |title=Anatomie eines Aufstandes: Dunkle Krawalle \u2013 Der Freitag |language=de |publisher=Freitag.de |accessdate=6 November 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/report/dissent-violently-repressed-cameroon-20090129 |title=Dissent violently repressed in Cameroon |accessdate=2010-12-04 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317052250/http://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/report/dissent-violently-repressed-cameroon-20090129 |archivedate=17 March 2011 |df=dmy }}. amnesty.org. 29 January 2009</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://report2009.amnesty.org/en/regions/africa/cameroon |title=Cameroon &#124; Amnesty International Report 2009 |publisher=Report2009.amnesty.org |accessdate=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008000900/http://report2009.amnesty.org/en/regions/africa/cameroon |archivedate=8 October 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> In 2009, his holiday in France allegedly cost $40,000 a day spent on 43 hotel rooms.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/8236962.stm \"Cameroon defends Biya hotel bills\"], BBC, 3 September 2009 {{in lang|fr}}.</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Biya was ranked 19th in ''[[Parade Magazine]]'s'' Top 20 list of \"The World's Worst Dictators\".<ref>[http://www.parade.com/dictators/ The World's Worst Dictators]. Parade.com (2011-10-20). Retrieved on 2011-11-08.</ref>\n\nIn November 2010, [[Bertrand Teyou]] published a book titled ''La belle de la r\u00e9publique banani\u00e8re: Chantal Biya, de la rue au palais'' (English: \"''The beauty of the banana republic: Chantal Biya, from the streets to the palace''\"), tracing Chantal Biya's rise from humble origins to become Paul Biya's First Lady.<ref name=\"PEN\">{{cite web |url=http://www.penusa.org/ran-1211 |title=CAMEROON: Author jailed for insulting President's wife |date=25 March 2011 |publisher=[[International PEN]] |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref> He was subsequently given a two-year prison term on charges of \"insult to character\" and organizing an \"illegal demonstration\" for attempting to hold a public reading.<ref name=\"PEN\" /> [[Amnesty International]] and [[International PEN]]'s Writers in Prison Committee both protested his arrest and issued appeals on his behalf; Amnesty International also named him a [[prisoner of conscience]].<ref name=\"PEN\" /><ref name=\"AI\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/afr17/001/2011/en/ |title=Urgent Action:CAMEROONIAN WRITER HELD IN HARSH CONDITIONS |date=12 April 2011 |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |accessdate=21 April 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> He was freed on 2 May 2011 when the London chapter of International PEN agreed to pay his fine in order that he might seek treatment for his worsening health condition.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.camerpress.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=543:cameroun-lecrivain-bertrand-teyou-sort-de-prison&catid=67:politique&Itemid=66 |title=Cameroun: L'\u00e9crivain Bertrand Teyou Sort De Prison |date=2 May 2011 |publisher=camerpress.net |accessdate=5 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2014, French citizen [[Michel Thierry Atangana]] was released from a makeshift [[Yaound\u00e9]] prison where, under Biya's orders, he had been arbitrarily detained for 17 years under false claims of embezzlement because of supposed closeness to presidential candidate [[Titus Edzoa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parismatch.com/Actu/Societe/Michel-Thierry-Atangana-le-citoyen-oublie-850735|title=Fran\u00e7ais emprisonn\u00e9 17 ans au Cameroun - Michel Thierry Atangana, le citoyen oubli\u00e9|first=Paris|last=Match|publisher=}}</ref> Considered a [[political prisoner]] and [[prisoner of conscience]] by the [[United States Department of State]], [[Amnesty International]], [[Freedom House]], and the U.N. [[Working Group on Arbitrary Detention]] since 2005,<ref>http://www.cameroon-info.net/stories/0,39574,@,cameroun-selon-amnesty-international-michel-atangana-prisonnier-d-opinion.html {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322034501/http://www.cameroon-info.net/stories/0%2C39574%2C%40%2Ccameroun-selon-amnesty-international-michel-atangana-prisonnier-d-opinion.html |date=22 March 2016 }}</ref> Michel was released under Biya's personal decree but the Working Group's tripartite demands remain unfulfilled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/wgad/38-2013.html|title=University of Minnesota Human Rights Library|website=www1.umn.edu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuneafrique.com/273095/societe/michel-thierry-atangana-dois-etre-rehabilite-reprendre-cours-de-vie/|title=Michel Thierry Atangana : \" Je dois \u00eatre r\u00e9habilit\u00e9 pour reprendre le cours de ma vie \" \u2013 JeuneAfrique.com|date=21 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 Cameroonians in the nation's capital city of Yaound\u00e9 criticized Biya's reaction to the country's worst train crash in which 79 people died. Criticism included government officials who remained anonymous, fearing a backlash.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/818654/cameroons-paul-biya-is-slammed-by-his-country-for-his-lukeware-reaction-to-the-eseka-train-crash/|title=Cameroonians are furious with their \u2018absent\u2019 president after a national tragedy|work=Quartz|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe Anglophone protests in late 2016 were led by English-speaking lawyers in protest against the use of French in Cameroonian courts, which led to violent clashes with police. Opposition party leader Edna Njilin of the Cameroon People's Party spoke out against the enforced use of French in the classroom. In January 2017, the government ordered a suspension of Internet services in the Northwest and Southwest provinces.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/02/03/africa/internet-shutdown-cameroon/index.html|title=Cameroon goes offline after Anglophone revolt|website=CNN|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref>  Criticism of the suspension and increased opposition led to resumption of services in late April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-39665244|title=Cameroon ends internet shutdown on orders of President Paul Biya|date=2017-04-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nBy June 2017, protests in Cameroon's English-speaking provinces and cities led to police responding with force, with 4 protesters killed and over 100 arrested. International criticism has been levied at the United States for their lack of response to the growing Cameroonian crisis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2017/06/02/cameroon-has-been-in-crisis-for-six-months-heres-what-you-need-to-know/|title=Analysis {{!}} Cameroon has been in crisis for six months. Here\u2019s what you need to know.|website=Washington Post|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, a Cameroonian journalist working for [[Radio France Internationale]], [[Ahmed Abba]], was sentenced to 10 years' imprisonment by a military tribunal for failing to report acts of terrorism. The judgement was severely criticized by human rights groups including Amnesty International.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.voanews.com/a/cameroon-journalist-jailed-for-ten-years-under-anti-terrorism-law/3824341.html|title=Cameroon Journalist Jailed for 10 Years Under Anti-terrorism Law|last=Reuters|work=VOA|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 November 2018, another Cameroonian journalist, Mimi Mefo, was arrested after reporting on social media that the Cameroonian military was behind the murder of an American missionary in the country, Charles Trumann, in October of that year.  Mefo was charged with \"publishing and propagating information that infringes on the territorial integrity of the Republic of Cameroon,\" but was released and charges were dropped on 12 November after her arrest was condemned by both local and international media groups.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-46194532|title=Cameroon drops fake news charges against Mimi Mefo|last=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-15|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Southern Cameroon ===\n\nIn early 2017, videos and reports surfaced online showing a genocide was taking place in Southern Cameroon,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cameroonconcordnews.com/crimes-against-humanity-and-genocide-in-southern-cameroons-mechanisms-for-redress/|title=Crimes against humanity and genocide in Southern Cameroons: Mechanisms for redress \u2013 Cameroon Concord News|website=www.cameroonconcordnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-06-28}}</ref> sanctioned and led by Paul Biya. A petition to the United Nations gave details of police raping students at a university.  Supporters are calling for the independence of Southern Cameroon before the violence escalates.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tribuneonlineng.com/southern-cameroonians-agitate-independence-republic-cameroon/|title=Southern Cameroonians agitate for independence from Republic of Cameroon - Tribune|date=2017-05-26|work=Tribune|access-date=2017-06-28|language=en-GB}}</ref> The National Commission for Human Rights and Freedoms embarked on a fact-finding mission in [[Buea]] to investigate allegations of human rights abuses in the region.\n\nMany allegations of indiscriminate killing, burning of villages, rape and humiliation of English-speaking citizens carried out by the BIR (Bataillon d'Intervention Rapide) have been made along with supporting video footage. The BIR is a special force body that reports directly to President Biya. Individual sources testify that all of those sent to fight the secessionist militia are French speaking, thus widening the linguistic division between local residents. [https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-africa-44584122/witnessing-cameroon-s-descent-towards-civil-war][https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2018/may/30/cameroon-killings-escalate-anglophone-crisis]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Paul Biya}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.prc.cm/en/}}\n*[http://www.worldstatesmen.org/Cameroon.html World Statesmen \u2013 Cameroon]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Simon Pierre Tchoungui]]|as=Prime Minister of East Cameroon}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[Prime Minister of Cameroon]]|years=1975\u20131982}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Bello Bouba Maigari]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Salomon Tandeng Muna]]|as=Prime Minister of West Cameroon}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ahmadou Ahidjo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of heads of state of Cameroon|President of Cameroon]]|years=1982\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CameroonPresidents}}\n{{CameroonPMs}}\n{{African Union chairpersons}}\n{{Commonwealth heads of government}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Biya, Paul}}\n[[Category:1933 births|Biya, Paul]]\n[[Category:Cameroon People's Democratic Movement politicians]]\n[[Category:Cameroonian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from South Region (Cameroon)]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Cameroon]]\n[[Category:Sciences Po alumni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses Special Class of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Order of Chad]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ouissam Alaouite]]\n", "name_user": "HaileJones", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Biya"}
{"title_page": "C\u00f3ndor Huasi", "text_new": "{{About|the village and municipality in Argentina|other uses|Kuntur Wasi (disambiguation){{!}}Kuntur Wasi (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          =C\u00f3ndor Huasi\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = Kuntur Wasi\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        =Municipality and village\n|motto                  =\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|pushpin_map            =\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize=\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       ={{flag|Argentina}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Argentina|Province]] \n|subdivision_name1      =[[Catamarca Province]]\n|subdivision_type2      =[[Departments of Argentina|Department]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      = \n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial \n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|population_as_of               =\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|27|28|59|S|67|04|59|W|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|elevation_m            = 1863\n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = K4751\n|area_code              = 03835\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''C\u00f3ndor Huasi''' (from [[Quechua language|Quechua]] ''Kuntur Wasi'', ''kuntur'' condor, ''wasi'' house,<ref>Teofilo Laime Ajacopa, Diccionario Biling\u00fce Iskay simipi yuyayk'ancha, La Paz, 2007 (Quechua-Spanish dictionary)</ref> \"condor house\") is a village and municipality in [[Catamarca Province]] in northwestern [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.mininterior.gov.ar/ Ministerio del Interior] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Condor Huasi}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Catamarca Province]]\n\n\n{{Catamarca-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the viallge and municipality in Argentina|other uses|Kuntur Wasi (disambiguation){{!}}Kuntur Wasi (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          =C\u00f3ndor Huasi\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            = Kuntur Wasi\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        =Municipality and village\n|motto                  =\n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \n|seal_size              =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|pushpin_map            =\n|pushpin_label_position =bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize=\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       ={{flag|Argentina}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Argentina|Province]] \n|subdivision_name1      =[[Catamarca Province]]\n|subdivision_type2      =[[Departments of Argentina|Department]]\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      = \n|subdivision_name3      = \n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      =  \n|established_date       = \n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                =Imperial \n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = \n|area_land_km2            = \n|population_as_of               =\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|27|28|59|S|67|04|59|W|display=inline}}\n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|elevation_m            = 1863\n|elevation_ft           = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = K4751\n|area_code              = 03835\n|blank_name             =\n|blank_info             =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''C\u00f3ndor Huasi''' (from [[Quechua language|Quechua]] ''Kuntur Wasi'', ''kuntur'' condor, ''wasi'' house,<ref>Teofilo Laime Ajacopa, Diccionario Biling\u00fce Iskay simipi yuyayk'ancha, La Paz, 2007 (Quechua-Spanish dictionary)</ref> \"condor house\") is a village and municipality in [[Catamarca Province]] in northwestern [[Argentina]].<ref>[http://www.mininterior.gov.ar/ Ministerio del Interior] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Condor Huasi}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Catamarca Province]]\n\n\n{{Catamarca-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: viallge \u2192 village", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%C3%B3ndor_Huasi"}
{"title_page": "Idiot Wind", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br />[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018. Some reviewers have speculated that the song is a reflection on Dylan's personal life, and in particular on his deteriorating relationship with his wife [[Sara Dylan]], whilst Dylan has denied that it is autobiographical.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from [[Sara Dylan]], who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2}}</ref>{{rp|160}} and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://archive.org/details/simpletwistoffat00gill|url-access=registration|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that \"Idiot Wind\" was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem ''June 1940'' by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|}}{{rp|140-141}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included only guitar and bass accompaniment, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind,\" in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u201325}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013347}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of \"Idiot Wind\" featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u201356}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn't stop. It wouldn't stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It's something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan's More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" />\n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\"{{efn|Sara Dylan was known as Sara Lownds before marrying Bob Dylan}} O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> David Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with \"Idiot Wind\" \u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played \"Idiot Wind\" in a show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|95}} This live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was also included on the Dylan album [[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]] that was released in Japan and Australia.<ref name=\"BJ762\" /><ref name=\"Bell2013\">{{cite book|author=Ian Bell|title=Time Out of Mind: The Lives of Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbx8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT614|date=12 September 2013|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-78057-835-4|page=614}}</ref>\n\nDylan has denied that the song refers to his personal life. In an interview with Bill Flanagan  Dylan said that although many people thought that \"Idiot Wind\" and the album ''Blood on the Tracks'' related to his life, \"It didn't pertain to me. It was just a concept of putting in images that defy time - yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wanted to make them all kind of connect in some kind of a strange way.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\" /> In his 2004 memoir ''[[Chronicles: Volume One]]'' Dylan claimed that ''Blood on the Tracks'' was \"an entire album based on [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] short stories. Critics thought it was autobiographical \u2013 that was fine.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and \"Idiot Wind\", which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We're idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of \"Idiot Wind\".\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0}}{{rp|95}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan's Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|page=257}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref> In a 2020 article for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] ranked it the third-greatest of Dylan's songs, praising it as \"extraordinary, harrowing listening\" and quoting the lyric \"I haven\u2019t known peace and quiet for so long I can\u2019t remember what it\u2019s like,\" commenting \"its author isn\u2019t just hurling bitter accusations, he\u2019s writhing in agony.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |title=Bob Dylan's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked!  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/09/bob-dylans-50-greatest-songs-ranked |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=9 April 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" /> When Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''The Guardian'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You're an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992, when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that \"Idiot Wind\" was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|129}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of \"Idiot Wind\" are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an opinion piece written in 2003 in response to [[Rasheed Wallace]]'s controversial comments in an interview with [[The Oregonian]], [[Bill Walton]] used some of the lyrics to \"Idiot Wind.\" <ref>{{Cite news|https://www.espn.com/nba/columns/story?columnist=walton_bill&id=1687101}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] picked out \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in [[Conor McPherson]]'s play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original 2017 London production at [[The Old Vic]] and the subsequent transfer to the [[West End theatre|West End]] it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], playing the role of Marianne Laine, as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"McPherson2017\">{{cite book|author=Conor McPherson|title=Girl from the North Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2FhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT9|date=20 November 2017|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|isbn=978-1-55936-882-7|page=9}}</ref><ref name=\"RWG\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bano |first=Tim |title=Girl from the North Country star Sheila Atim: 'You don't want to be a freedom fighter every time you enter a job' |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |work=The Stage |date=15 January 2019 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Atim won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"BJ762\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Bell2013\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Sonny Lubick Field at Hughes Stadium|Hughes Stadium]] || 23 May 1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, [[Scarlet Rivera]]: violin; [[T Bone Burnett|T-bone J. Henry Burnett]]: guitar, piano; [[Steven Soles]]: guitar; [[Mick Ronson]]: guitar; [[Bob Neuwirth|Bobby Neuwirth]]: guitar, vocals; [[Roger McGuinn]]: guitar, vocals; [[David Mansfield]]: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; [[Rob Stoner]]: bass; [[Howard Wyeth|Howie Wyeth]]: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || \n|-\n| 3 || ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' || 1978 || Hughes Stadium || 23 May 1976 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, Scarlet Rivera: violin; T-bone J. Henry Burnett: guitar, piano; Steven Soles: guitar; Mick Ronson: guitar; Bobby Neuwirth: guitar, vocals; Roger McGuinn: guitar, vocals; David Mansfield: steel guitar, mandolin, violin, dobro; Rob Stoner: bass; Howie Wyeth: drums; Gary Burke: percussion || Previously released on ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''. ''[[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]]'' was released in 1978 in Japan and Australia.\n|-\n| 4 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' || 1991 || [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]] || 19 September 1974 || 4 (remake) \u2013 with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass. Organ overdub by [[Paul Griffin (musician)|Paul Griffin]].<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /> || \n|-\n| 5 || ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' || 2018 || A&R Studios|| 19 September 1974 || 4 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 6 || rowspan=\"9\" | ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]] (Deluxe edition)'' || rowspan=\"9\" | 2018 || A&R Studios || 16 September 1974 || 1 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 7 || A&R Studios || 16 September 1974 || 1 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 8 ||  A&R Studios || 16 September 1974 || 3 (with insert) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 9 ||  A&R Studios || 16 September 1974 || 5 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 10 || A&R Studios || 16 September 1974 || 6 || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 11 || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || Rehearsal and Takes 1\u20133, Remake || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 12 || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || 4 (remake) || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || \n|-\n| 13 || A&R Studios || 19 September 1974 || 4 (remake) \u2013 with organ overdub || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica; Tony Brown: bass || Previously released on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]''\n|-\n| 14 || Sound 80 || 27 December 1974 ||  || \"Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; Billy Peterson: bass; Bill Berg: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''\n|-\n| 15 || ''The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.legacyrecordings.co.uk/news/music-inspired-girl-north-country-now |title=The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country \u2013 Out Now |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=18 January 2018 |website=legacyrecordings.co.uk |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> || 2018 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums || Previously released on ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/bob-dylans-music-inspired-girl-north-country-announced-102635/ |title=Bob Dylan's The Music Which Inspired Girl From The North Country announced |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=19 December 2017 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Covers==\n[[Mary Lee's Corvette]] covered the entire ''Blood on The Tracks'' album in 2002, including \"Idiot Wind\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/mary-lees-corvette-blood-on-the-tracks-28113/ |title=Mary Lee's Corvette \u2013 Blood on the Tracks |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=1 February 2003 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Covers of \"Idiot Wind\" were also included on [[Phil Pritchett]]'s album ''Blueprint Garage Volume 2''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deezer.com/en/track/77303011 |title=Idiot Wind: Phil Pritchett |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=deezer.com |publisher=Deezer |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> and the [[Coal Porters]] album ''How Dark This Earth Will Shine''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/bob-dylan-uncut-january-2005-cds-44438/ |title=Bob Dylan \u2013 Uncut January 2005 CDs |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=10 November 2004 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe original cast recording of ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]'', recorded at [[Abbey Road Studios]], includes the song. As in the original London production of the play, it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"RWG\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oldvictheatre.com/news/2017/08/the-girl-from-the-north-country-cast-recording |title=The Girl from the North Country cast recording is here |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=30 August 2017 |website=oldvictheatre.com |publisher=The Old Vic |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind Lyrics to \"Idiot Wind\"]\n\n{{Bob Dylan}}\n\n[[Category:Songs written by Bob Dylan]]\n[[Category:Bob Dylan songs]]\n[[Category:1975 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Bob Dylan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{for|the Swedish artist|Amanda Bergman}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Idiot Wind\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| caption  = Album cover\n| artist   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| album    = [[Blood on the Tracks]]\n| released = January 1975\n| recorded = 27 December 1974\n| studio   = [[Sound 80]],<br />[[Minneapolis, Minnesota]]\n| venue    = \n| genre    = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length   = 7:48\n| label    = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer   = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| producer = [[Bob Dylan]]\n| tracks   = {{Blood on the Tracks tracks}}\n}}\n\"'''Idiot Wind'''\" is a song by [[Bob Dylan]], which appeared on his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.  The song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year. Dylan recorded the song in September 1974, but as with some other songs from ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'', re-recorded it in December 1974. Between the recordings, he often reworked the lyrics. A live version of the song was released on Dylan's 1976 album ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'', and all of the studio outtakes from the September sessions were released on the deluxe edition of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'' in 2018. Some reviewers have speculated that the song is a reflection on Dylan's personal life, and in particular on his deteriorating relationship with his wife [[Sara Dylan]], whilst Dylan has denied that it is autobiographical.\n\n== Background and recording ==\nThe song was written, or at least begun, in the summer of 1974, after Dylan's [[Bob Dylan and The Band 1974 Tour|comeback tour]] with [[The Band]] that year and a separation from [[Sara Dylan]], who he had married in 1965. Dylan had moved to a farm in Minnesota with his brother, David Zimmerman and there started to write the songs that were recorded for his album ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]''.<ref name=\"UNCUT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656/ |title=Shelter From The Storm \u2013 the inside story of Bob Dylan's Blood on the Tracks |last=Hasted |first=Nick |date=15 November 2013 |work=Uncut |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180715011356/https://www.uncut.co.uk/features/shelter-from-the-storm-the-inside-story-of-bob-dylan-s-blood-on-the-tracks-15656 |archive-date=15 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the Spring of 1974, Dylan had taken art classes at [[Carnegie Hall]] and was influenced by his tutor [[Norman Raeben]].<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Rogovoy2009\">{{cite book|author=Seth Rogovoy|title=Bob Dylan: Prophet, Mystic, Poet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IdbgeObYgIkC&pg=PA160|date=24 November 2009|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-5983-2}}</ref>{{rp|160}} and, in particular, Raeben's view of [[time]].<ref name=\"GillOdegard2004\">{{cite book|author1=Andy Gill|author2=Kevin Odegard|title=A Simple Twist of Fate: Bob Dylan and the Making of Blood on the Tracks|url=https://archive.org/details/simpletwistoffat00gill|url-access=registration|date=January 2004|publisher=Da Capo Press|isbn=978-0-306-81231-6}}</ref> Dylan was later to say that \"Idiot Wind\" was \"a song I wanted to make as a painting.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\">{{cite book|author=Bill Flanagan|title=Written in My Soul: Conversations with Rock's Great Songwriters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|date=1 April 2010|publisher=RosettaBooks|isbn=978-0-7953-1081-2|access-date=6 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506011534/https://books.google.com/books?id=BUAqAAAAQBAJ|archive-date=6 May 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \"Idiot Wind\" was a derogatory phrase employed by Raeben and this may have inspired Dylan's use of it, although the term also appears in the poem ''June 1940'' by [[Weldon Kees]] and that may have been the reference point.<ref name=\"Wilentz2011\">{{cite book|author=Sean Wilentz|title=Bob Dylan in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sb5UygkZlH0C&pg=PA140|date=15 February 2011|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-1-4070-7411-5|}}{{rp|140-141}}</ref>\n\nDylan first recorded \"Idiot Wind\" in New York City on 12 September 1974 during the initial ''Blood on the Tracks'' sessions at [[A & R Recording|A&R Studios]]. The first recording included only guitar and bass accompaniment, with organ later [[Overdubbing|overdubbed]]. That December, working from a suggestion from his brother that the album should have a more commercial sound, Dylan re-recorded half the songs on ''Blood on the Tracks'', including \"Idiot Wind,\" in Minneapolis.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\" /><ref name=\"OHAGAN\">{{cite news |last=O'Hagan |first=Sean |title=The raw, painful birth of Blood on the Tracks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=28 October 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417055617/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2018/oct/28/bob-dylan-more-blood-more-tracks-raw-painful-birth |archive-date=17 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Chris |title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks Review |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |work=BBC |year=2007 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190919065715/http://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/659x/ |archive-date=19 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Creswell2007\">{{cite book|author=Toby Creswell|title=1001 Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bhYnNaM0zEUC&pg=PA24|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hardie Grant Publishing|isbn=1-74273-148-1|pages=24\u201325}}</ref> The New York sessions were engineered by [[Phil Ramone]]. In New York, Dylan's guitar was tuned to [[Open D tuning|open D]] with a [[capo]] on the second [[fret]] so that all of the songs were in the [[Key (music)|key]] of E.<ref name=\"Wise2017\">{{cite book|author=Wise Publications|title=Bob Dylan: Blood On The Tracks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fEejDgAAQBAJ|date=8 April 2017|publisher=Wise Publications|isbn=978-1-78323-916-0}}</ref> Paul Martinson was the engineer for the Minneapolis sessions.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" />\n\nThe re-recorded versions were radical departures from the original recordings, and each new recording included changes to the lyrics from the earlier versions.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /><ref name=\"Dalton2012\">{{cite book|author=David Dalton|title=Who Is That Man? In Search of the Real Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SDcDAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT346|date=1 June 2012|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-779-2|pages=346\u2013347}}</ref> The September 1974 recording of \"Idiot Wind\" featured just acoustic guitar and bass instrumentation, whereas the re-recording made on 27 December 1974 and issued on ''Blood on the Tracks'', featured a full band. This group of local musicians had been hurriedly been put together, and Dylan had not previously met them.<ref name=\"UNCUT\" /><ref name=\"AMSO\" /> The Minneapolis recordings are in [[standard tuning]].<ref name=\"Wise2017\" /> [[Clinton Heylin]] recounts that Dylan frequently reworked the song from September to December.<ref name=\"Heylin2010\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Still on the Road: The Songs of Bob Dylan Vol. 2 1974-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jaSeBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT55|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Little, Brown Book Group|isbn=978-1-84901-494-6|pages=55\u201356}}</ref> In a 1991 interview with [[Paul Zollo]], Dylan said that there could be many more verses for the song and that it could be constantly reworked.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/7/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020 |quote=\"there could be a myriad of verses for the thing. It doesn't stop. It wouldn't stop. Where do you end? You could still be writing it, really. It's something that could be a work continually in progress.\"}}</ref> Zollo contrasts the ''Blood on the Tracks'' version with the one from ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' which was Take 4, with added organ overdubs, recorded on 19 September 1974 in New York, and opines that the gentler delivery of the song in the September version \"makes the inherent disquiet of the song even more disturbing.\"<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uncut.co.uk/news/read-complete-tracklisting-bob-dylans-blood-tracks-bootleg-series-vol-14-107408/ |title=Read the complete tracklisting for Bob Dylan's More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 |last=Bonner |first=Michael |date=20 September 2018 |work=Uncut |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ZOLLO2\" />\n\nIndividual outtakes from the New York sessions were released in 1991 on ''[[The Bootleg Series Volumes 1\u20133 (Rare & Unreleased) 1961\u20131991]]'' and in 2018 on the single-CD and 2-LP versions of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', while the complete New York sessions were released on the deluxe edition of the latter album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The deluxe version of  ''The Bootleg Series Vol. 14'' also included a remix of the December 1974 master issued on ''Blood on the Tracks''.<ref name=\"MBMTREL\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|title=More Blood, More Tracks \u2013 The Bootleg Series Vol. 14 to Be Released on November 2 {{!}} The Official Bob Dylan Site|website=www.bobdylan.com|access-date=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181105064613/https://www.bobdylan.com/news/more-blood-more-tracks-the-bootleg-series-vol-14-to-be-released-on-november-2/|archive-date=5 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> A live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''.<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretations ==\nBarbara O'Dair (2009) links the song to two of Dylan's other compositions, \"Sad Eyed Lady of the Lowlands\" (1966) and \"Sara\" (1976) as a set of songs written across ten years \"addressing a woman that bears a resemblance to his now ex-wife Sara Lowndes.\"{{efn|Sara Dylan was known as Sara Lownds before marrying Bob Dylan}} O'Dair criticises the song for [[victim blaming]].<ref name=\"ODAIR2009\">{{cite book |last=O'Dair |first=Barbara |editor-last1=Dettmar |editor-first1=Kevin |title=The Cambridge Companion to Bob Dylan |page= 83 |chapter=Bob Dylan and gender politics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=73eAjOofhCAC|date=19 February 2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-82843-7}}</ref> David Goldblatt and Edward Necarsulmer (2011) say that in the song, Dylan \"explores the bitterness of resentment and revenge against a lover and against one's own love who botched their love.\"<ref name=\"PVI2011\">{{cite book |last1=Goldblatt |first1=David |last2=Necarsulmer IV |first2=Edward |editor-last1=Porter |editor-first1=Carl J. |editor-last2=Vernezze |editor-first2=Peter |editor-last3=Irwin |editor-first3=William |title=Bob Dylan and Philosophy: It's Alright Ma (I'm Only Thinking) |publisher=Open Court |date=2011 |page=163 |chapter=Language on the Lam(b): Tarantula in Dylan and Nietzsche |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JaOqtb977hQC |isbn=978-0-8126-9760-5 |lastauthoramp=y}}</ref> Dylan has denied that the song is personal, stating in 1985 that:<ref name=\"WILLMAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |title=Dylan's blood-best album: 40 facts about the 40-year-old Blood On The Tracks |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=21 January 2015 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405155031/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/dylans-bloody-best-album-40-facts-about-the-40-year-old-blood-on-the-tracks-159901/ |archive-date=5 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I thought I might have gone a little bit too far with \"Idiot Wind\" \u2026 I didn't really think I was giving away too much; I thought that it seemed so personal that people would think it was about so-and-so who was close to me. It wasn't \u2026 I didn't feel that one was too personal, but I felt it seemed too personal. Which might be the same thing, I don't know.\"}}\n\nTimothy Hampton takes the song as political, and a commentary on the [[Vietnam War]],<ref name=\"Hampton2019\">{{cite book|author=Timothy Hampton|title=Bob Dylan's Poetics: How the Songs Work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51WRDwAAQBAJ|date=26 March 2019|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-1-942130-15-4}}</ref> whereas David Dalton feels that Dylan draws parallels between his personal situation and the national one, and \"turns his own fate into an allegory of the soured American dream.\"<ref name=\"Dalton2012\" />\n\nDylan and Lowndes' relationship deteriorated in 1976, and David Kinney relates how Dylan played \"Idiot Wind\" in a show at Fort Collins whilst Lowndes was in the audience, noting in the following sentence that the pair were divorced the following year.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|95}} This live version from 23 May 1976 is included as the closing track to ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]''<ref name=\"WILLMAN\" /><ref name=\"Heylin2011\">{{cite book|author=Clinton Heylin|title=Behind the Shades: The 20th Anniversary Edition|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dd5EmZDdScoC&pg=PA369|date=1 April 2011|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=978-0-571-27241-9|page=440}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |title=Hard Rain (1976) |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102220420/http://www.bobdylan.com/albums/hard-rain/ |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and was also included on the Dylan album [[Masterpieces (Bob Dylan album)|Masterpieces]] that was released in Japan and Australia.<ref name=\"BJ762\" /><ref name=\"Bell2013\">{{cite book|author=Ian Bell|title=Time Out of Mind: The Lives of Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bbx8AAAAQBAJ&pg=PT614|date=12 September 2013|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|isbn=978-1-78057-835-4|page=614}}</ref>\n\nDylan has denied that the song refers to his personal life. In an interview with Bill Flanagan  Dylan said that although many people thought that \"Idiot Wind\" and the album ''Blood on the Tracks'' related to his life, \"It didn't pertain to me. It was just a concept of putting in images that defy time - yesterday, today and tomorrow. I wanted to make them all kind of connect in some kind of a strange way.\"<ref name=\"Flanagan2010\" /> In his 2004 memoir ''[[Chronicles: Volume One]]'' Dylan claimed that ''Blood on the Tracks'' was \"an entire album based on [[Anton Chekhov|Chekhov]] short stories. Critics thought it was autobiographical \u2013 that was fine.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" />\n\n==Critical reception==\nThe album ''Blood on the Tracks'' received mixed reviews on release.<ref name=\"Williamson2004\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Williamson|title=The Rough Guide to Bob Dylan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R2c8AQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Rough Guides|isbn=978-1-84353-139-5}}</ref> ''Rolling Stone'' carried two reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-lists/10-classic-albums-rolling-stone-originally-panned-101316/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-1975-101880/ |title=10 Classic Albums Rolling Stone Originally Panned  |last=Greene |first=Andy |date=25 July 2016 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Jonathan Cott described the album as \"magnificent and memorable\" and \"Idiot Wind\", which he saw as equally as accomplished as the other songs, as \"explosive and bitter.\" Cott observed that it was the first time that Dylan had included himself in a condemnation in one of his songs, with the line \"We're idiots, babe/It's a wonder we can even feed ourselves.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/bob-dylan-blood-on-the-tracks-55031/  |title=Bob Dylan: Blood on the Tracks  |last=Cott |first=Jonathan |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, in the other ''Rolling Stone'' review, [[Jon Landau]] disparaged \"the childishness (without any redeeming childlike wonder) of so much of \"Idiot Wind\".\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |title=Blood on the Tracks |last=Landau |first=Jon |date=13 March 1975 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230122112/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/blood-on-the-tracks-255430/ |archive-date=30 December 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Lester Bangs]] originally regarded the song as \"absurdly spiteful\" and was unimpressed, although he soon found himself listening to the album frequently.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\">{{cite book|author=David Kinney|title=The Dylanologists: Adventures in the Land of Bob|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2TBvAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA129|date=13 May 2014|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4516-2694-0}}{{rp|95}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2003 book ''[[Dylan's Visions of Sin]]'', [[Christopher Ricks|Professor Christopher Ricks]] discusses a particular lyrical couplet from the song, namely: \"Blowing like a circle around my skull/From the [[Grand Coulee Dam]] to the [[United States Capitol|Capitol]].\" Ricks praises this as \"fierce \u2026 And it's a true rhyme because of the metaphorical relation, because of what a head of state is, and the body politic, and because of the relation of the Capitol to the skull (another of those white domes), with which it disconcertingly rhymes. An imperfect rhyme, perfectly judged.\"<ref name=\"Ricks2011\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Ricks|title=Dylan's Visions of Sin|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jlDWua9p8lEC|date=5 May 2011|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-0-85786-202-0}}</ref> The same rhyme had impressed [[Allen Ginsberg]], who wrote to Dylan comparing it to an image from [[The Bridge (long poem)|The Bridge]] by [[Hart Crane]]. Dylan was apparently gratified to receive Ginsberg's letter, and it was a contributing factor in leading to Ginsberg being invited onto the [[Rolling Thunder Revue]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/on-the-road-with-bob-dylan-joan-baez-and-the-rolling-thunder-revue-183508/ |title=On the Road With Bob Dylan, Joan Baez and the Rolling Thunder Revue  |last=Hentoff |first=Nat |date=15 January 1976 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> In his 1976 review in ''[[The Village Voice]]'', Paul Cowan also referred to these lyrics, saying that they evoked both [[Woody Guthrie]] in the language used and [[T.S. Elliot]] in the delivery of the vocal. Like Cott, Cowan noted the ultimately self-accusatory nature of the lyrics, which he felt provided a surprising conclusion to the song.<ref name=\"COWAN\">{{cite web |url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |title=Riffs: Bob Dylan's Pain \u2014 Flip Side of Cruelty |last=Cowan |first=Paul |date=3 February 1975 |work=The Village Voice |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316142900/https://www.villagevoice.com/2020/02/13/bob-dylans-pain-flip-side-of-cruelty/ |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The lyrics referencing the Capitol replaced the earlier \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your jaw/From the Grand Coulee Dam to the [[Mardi Gras]]\" used in New York.<ref name=\"Burger2018\">{{cite book|author=Jeff Burger|title=Dylan on Dylan: Interviews and Encounters|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kVo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT257|date=1 May 2018|publisher=Chicago Review Press|isbn=978-0-912777-44-3|page=257}}</ref> Zollo also felt that this pair of lines was the highlight of the song.<ref name=\"ZOLLO2\">{{cite web |url=https://americansongwriter.com/bob-dylan-the-paul-zollo-interview-3/2/ |title=Bob Dylan: The Paul Zollo Interview |last=Zollo |first=Paul |date=9 January 2012 |orig-year=1991 |website=americansongwriter.com |publisher=American Songwriter |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[1001 Songs]]'', [[Toby Creswell]] says that the track is an \"epic of elegantly phrased bile\" and is \"not based on logical exposition.\"<ref name=\"Creswell2007\" /> The song was 16th on '' [[American Songwriter]]'' magazine's 2009 ranking of ''The 30 Greatest Dylan Songs''.<ref name=\"AMSO\">{{cite web|url=https://americansongwriter.com/the-30-greatest-bob-dylan-songs-16-idiot-wind/|title=The 30 Greatest Bob Dylan Songs: #16, \"Idiot Wind\"|author=Schlansky, Evan|date=20 April 2009|publisher=americansongwriter.com|accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> and placed fourth in Jim Beviglia's 2013 book ''Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs''.<ref name=\"Beviglia2013\">{{cite book|author=Jim Beviglia|title=Counting Down Bob Dylan: His 100 Finest Songs|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nRMeAAAAQBAJ|date=11 July 2013|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-8824-1}}</ref> In a 2020 article for ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Alexis Petridis]] ranked it the third-greatest of Dylan's songs, praising it as \"extraordinary, harrowing listening\" and quoting the lyric \"I haven\u2019t known peace and quiet for so long I can\u2019t remember what it\u2019s like,\" commenting \"its author isn\u2019t just hurling bitter accusations, he\u2019s writhing in agony.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Petridis |first=Alexis |title=Bob Dylan's 50 greatest songs \u2013 ranked!  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/09/bob-dylans-50-greatest-songs-ranked |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=9 April 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\nIn a review of ''[[The Bootleg Series Vol. 14: More Blood, More Tracks]]'', Sean O'Hagan remarked of the song \"By turns paranoid, derisory and vengeful, it is a dark masterpiece of venomous intent, a great part of its raw power resting in the very discomfort the listener feels as it gathers momentum and the tone becomes ever more bitter.\"<ref name=\"OHAGAN\" /> When Dylan won the [[Nobel prize for literature]] in 2016, ''The Guardian'' cited \"Idiot wind, blowing every time you move your teeth/ You're an idiot, babe/ It's a wonder that you still know how to breathe\" from \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his greatest lyrics.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Are these the lyrics that won Bob Dylan a Nobel prize? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=13 October 2016 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521040933/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2016/oct/13/are-these-the-lyrics-that-won-bob-dylan-a-nobel-prize |archive-date=21 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Live performances==\nDylan played the song live 55 times between 18 April 1976, when it was first included in his set, at Civic Centre, Lakeland, Florida; and 30 August 1992, when he played it at the Orpheum Theatre, Minneapolis. 1976 and 1992 were the only years in which it featured in his live shows. As of April 2020, he has not performed it live since 1992.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |title=Setlists |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902230721/http://www.bobdylan.com/setlists/?id_song=26007 |archive-date=2 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, [[Clinton Heylin]], a prolific author of material about Dylan, flew from England to California to attend Dylan's shows when he heard that \"Idiot Wind\" was being played live again.<ref name=\"Kinney2014\" />{{rp|129}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nArtist Mohammad Omer Khalil produced a series of etchings, inspired by Dylan's music, that were displayed at the [[National Museum of African Art]] in 1994, including one entitled Idiot Wind.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://africa.si.edu/collections/view/objects/asitem/People@120/2?t:state:flow=847c62c4-c3b4-469a-baaf-52952b9c28ed |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=africa.si.edu |publisher=National Museum of African Art |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome of the lyrics of \"Idiot Wind\" are mentioned in the 1995 song \"[[Only Wanna Be with You]]\" by American band [[Hootie & the Blowfish]]. The use of Dylan's lyrics reportedly led to an out-of-court settlement, with Dylan receiving money from Hootie & the Blowfish.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|title=Darius Rucker on 'Wagon Wheel' and the Future of Hootie|last=Greene|first=Andy|date=19 July 2013|work=Rolling Stone|access-date=23 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181023200015/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/darius-rucker-on-wagon-wheel-and-the-future-of-hootie-234316/|archive-date=23 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSwedish musician [[Amanda Bergman]] used to perform under the stage name ''Idiot Wind''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|title = The shark that became Jaw Lesson is now Idiot Wind|date = 13 September 2010|website = svt.se|publisher = Swedish Television|last = Beckman|first = Eva|language = Swedish|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120426205311/http://blogg.svt.se/psl/2010/09/13/hajen-som-blev-jaw-lesson-blir-nu-idiot-wind/|archivedate = 26 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a reply to a question on the \"Ask Lou\" section of his website in 2007, singer-songwriter [[Lou Reed]] picked out \"Idiot Wind\" as the song he wished he had written.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |work=loureed.com |title=Ask Lou |date=December 2007 |access-date=12 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415130637/http://www.loureed.com/forum/index.php?p=%2Fdiscussion%2F2%2Fask-lou%2Fp1 |archive-date=15 April 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Novelist [[Peter Carey (novelist)|Peter Carey]] included \"Idiot Wind\" as one of his eight records for [[Desert Island Discs]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00c1q5q |title=Peter Carey |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=20 June 2008 |website=bbc.co.uk |publisher=BBC Radio 4 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe song appears in [[Conor McPherson]]'s play ''[[Girl from the North Country (play)|Girl from the North Country]]''. In the original 2017 London production at [[The Old Vic]] and the subsequent transfer to the [[West End theatre|West End]] it was sung by [[Sheila Atim]], playing the role of Marianne Laine, as part of a medley with ''[[Hurricane (Bob Dylan song)|Hurricane]]'' and ''[[All Along the Watchtower]]'' sung by [[Arinz\u00e9 Kene]].<ref name=\"McPherson2017\">{{cite book|author=Conor McPherson|title=Girl from the North Country|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2FhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PT9|date=20 November 2017|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|isbn=978-1-55936-882-7|page=9}}</ref><ref name=\"RWG\">{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Richard |title=Girl from the North Country lets us hear Bob Dylan's mysteries anew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |work=The Guardian |location=London |date=17 January 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406150058/https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2018/jan/17/girl-from-the-north-country-bob-dylan-london-theatre |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bano |first=Tim |title=Girl from the North Country star Sheila Atim: 'You don't want to be a freedom fighter every time you enter a job' |url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/features/interviews/2019/girl-north-country-star-sheila-atim-time-is-love-les-blancs-game-of-thrones/ |work=The Stage |date=15 January 2019 |access-date=7 April 2020}}</ref> Atim won the 2018 Laurence Olivier Award for Best Supporting Actress in a Musical for her role.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Olivier Awards 2018: Winners in full |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |work=BBC News |date=9 April 2018 |access-date=5 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930235126/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-43668013 |archive-date=30 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nPeter Kaldheim's 2019 novel ''Idiot Wind: A Memoir'' was published by Canongate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|title=Idiot Wind by Peter Kaldheim \u2013 Canongate Books|website=canongate.co.uk|access-date=15 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190715152051/https://canongate.co.uk/books/2859-idiot-wind-a-memoir/|archive-date=15 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |title=In Idiot Wind, a Lost Soul Finds His Way Home |last=Williams |first=John |date=28 July 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=6 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729233051/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/28/books/idiot-wind-peter-kaldheim.html |archive-date=29 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Releases==\nThe officially released versions of the song on Bob Dylan albums are below.<ref name=\"UNCUTMBMT\" /><ref name=\"MBMTREL\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bobdylan.com/songs/idiot-wind/ |title=Idiot Wind |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bobdylan.com |publisher=Sony Music Entertainment |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"BJ762\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/76-2.htm |title=1976 soon to be divorced |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bjorner.com/DSN03275%201976%20Rolling%20Thunder%20Revue%20II.htm |title=Still on the road: 1976 Rolling Thunder Revue II |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=bjorner.com |publisher=Olof Bjorner |access-date=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Bell2013\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!  !! Album !! Release Year !! Recorded at !! Recording date !! [[Take]] !! Personnel !! Notes\n|-\n| 1 || ''[[Blood on the Tracks]]'' || 1975 || [[Sound 80]] || 27 December 1974 ||  || Bob Dylan: vocals, guitar, harmonica, organ; Chris Weber: guitar; Gregg Inhofer: keyboards; [[Billy Peterson]]: bass; [[Bill Berg (musician)|Bill Berg]]: drums ||\n|-\n| 2 || ''[[Hard Rain (Bob Dylan album)|Hard Rain]]'' || 1976 || [[Son